55 // How the nonfinite values Inf and NaN are represented.
56 enum class fltNonfiniteBehavior {
57  // Represents standard IEEE 754 behavior. A value is nonfinite if the
58  // exponent field is all 1s. In such cases, a value is Inf if the
59  // significand bits are all zero, and NaN otherwise
60  IEEE754,
61 
62  // This behavior is present in the Float8ExMyFN* types (Float8E4M3FN,
63  // Float8E5M2FNUZ, and Float8E4M3FNUZ). There is no representation for Inf,
64  // and operations that would ordinarily produce Inf produce NaN instead.
65  // The details of the NaN representation(s) in this form are determined by the
66  // `fltNanEncoding` enum. We treat all NaNs as quiet, as the available
67  // encodings do not distinguish between signalling and quiet NaN.
68  NanOnly,
69 };
70 
71 // How NaN values are represented. This is curently only used in combination
72 // with fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly, and using a variant other than IEEE
73 // while having IEEE non-finite behavior is liable to lead to unexpected
74 // results.
75 enum class fltNanEncoding {
76  // Represents the standard IEEE behavior where a value is NaN if its
77  // exponent is all 1s and the significand is non-zero.
78  IEEE,
79 
80  // Represents the behavior in the Float8E4M3 floating point type where NaN is
81  // represented by having the exponent and mantissa set to all 1s.
82  // This behavior matches the FP8 E4M3 type described in
83  // https://arxiv.org/abs/2209.05433. We treat both signed and unsigned NaNs
84  // as non-signalling, although the paper does not state whether the NaN
85  // values are signalling or not.
86  AllOnes,
87 
88  // Represents the behavior in Float8E{5,4}E{2,3}FNUZ floating point types
89  // where NaN is represented by a sign bit of 1 and all 0s in the exponent
90  // and mantissa (i.e. the negative zero encoding in a IEEE float). Since
91  // there is only one NaN value, it is treated as quiet NaN. This matches the
92  // behavior described in https://arxiv.org/abs/2206.02915 .
93  NegativeZero,
94 };

96 /* Represents floating point arithmetic semantics. */
97 struct fltSemantics {
98  /* The largest E such that 2^E is representable; this matches the
99  definition of IEEE 754. */
100  APFloatBase::ExponentType maxExponent;
101 
102  /* The smallest E such that 2^E is a normalized number; this
103  matches the definition of IEEE 754. */
104  APFloatBase::ExponentType minExponent;
105 
106  /* Number of bits in the significand. This includes the integer
107  bit. */
108  unsigned int precision;
109 
110  /* Number of bits actually used in the semantics. */
111  unsigned int sizeInBits;
112 
113  fltNonfiniteBehavior nonFiniteBehavior = fltNonfiniteBehavior::IEEE754;
114 
115  fltNanEncoding nanEncoding = fltNanEncoding::IEEE;
116  // Returns true if any number described by this semantics can be precisely
117  // represented by the specified semantics. Does not take into account
118  // the value of fltNonfiniteBehavior.
119  bool isRepresentableBy(const fltSemantics &S) const {
120  return maxExponent <= S.maxExponent && minExponent >= S.minExponent &&
121  precision <= S.precision;
122  }
123 };

144  /* The IBM double-double semantics. Such a number consists of a pair of IEEE
145  64-bit doubles (Hi, Lo), where |Hi| > |Lo|, and if normal,
146  (double)(Hi + Lo) == Hi. The numeric value it's modeling is Hi + Lo.
147  Therefore it has two 53-bit mantissa parts that aren't necessarily adjacent
148  to each other, and two 11-bit exponents.
149 
150  Note: we need to make the value different from semBogus as otherwise
151  an unsafe optimization may collapse both values to a single address,
152  and we heavily rely on them having distinct addresses. */
153  static const fltSemantics semPPCDoubleDouble = {-1, 0, 0, 128};
154 
155  /* These are legacy semantics for the fallback, inaccrurate implementation of
156  IBM double-double, if the accurate semPPCDoubleDouble doesn't handle the
157  operation. It's equivalent to having an IEEE number with consecutive 106
158  bits of mantissa and 11 bits of exponent.
159 
160  It's not equivalent to IBM double-double. For example, a legit IBM
161  double-double, 1 + epsilon:
162 
163  1 + epsilon = 1 + (1 >> 1076)
164 
165  is not representable by a consecutive 106 bits of mantissa.
166 
167  Currently, these semantics are used in the following way:
168 
169  semPPCDoubleDouble -> (IEEEdouble, IEEEdouble) ->
170  (64-bit APInt, 64-bit APInt) -> (128-bit APInt) ->
171  semPPCDoubleDoubleLegacy -> IEEE operations
172 
173  We use bitcastToAPInt() to get the bit representation (in APInt) of the
174  underlying IEEEdouble, then use the APInt constructor to construct the
175  legacy IEEE float.
176 
177  TODO: Implement all operations in semPPCDoubleDouble, and delete these
178  semantics. */
179  static const fltSemantics semPPCDoubleDoubleLegacy = {1023, -1022 + 53,
180  53 + 53, 128};

183  switch (S) {
184  case S_IEEEhalf:

186  case S_BFloat:
187  return BFloat();

189  return IEEEsingle();
190  case S_IEEEdouble:
191  return IEEEdouble();

193  return IEEEquad();

210  APFloatBase::Semantics
211  APFloatBase::SemanticsToEnum(const llvm::fltSemantics &Sem) {
212  if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEhalf())
213  return S_IEEEhalf;
214  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::BFloat())
215  return S_BFloat;
216  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEsingle())
217  return S_IEEEsingle;
218  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEdouble())
219  return S_IEEEdouble;
220  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::IEEEquad())
221  return S_IEEEquad;
222  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::PPCDoubleDouble())
223  return S_PPCDoubleDouble;
224  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::Float8E5M2())
225  return S_Float8E5M2;
226  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::Float8E5M2FNUZ())
227  return S_Float8E5M2FNUZ;
228  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::Float8E4M3FN())
229  return S_Float8E4M3FN;
230  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::Float8E4M3FNUZ())
231  return S_Float8E4M3FNUZ;
232  else if (&Sem == &llvm::APFloat::x87DoubleExtended())
233  return S_x87DoubleExtended;
234  else
235  llvm_unreachable("Unknown floating semantics");
236  }

273  /* A tight upper bound on number of parts required to hold the value
274  pow(5, power) is
275 
276  power * 815 / (351 * integerPartWidth) + 1
277 
278  However, whilst the result may require only this many parts,
279  because we are multiplying two values to get it, the
280  multiplication may require an extra part with the excess part
281  being zero (consider the trivial case of 1 * 1, tcFullMultiply
282  requires two parts to hold the single-part result). So we add an
283  extra one to guarantee enough space whilst multiplying. */
284  const unsigned int maxExponent = 16383;
285  const unsigned int maxPrecision = 113;
286  const unsigned int maxPowerOfFiveExponent = maxExponent + maxPrecision - 1;
287  const unsigned int maxPowerOfFiveParts = 2 + ((maxPowerOfFiveExponent * 815) / (351 * APFloatBase::integerPartWidth));
288

303  unsigned int APFloatBase::semanticsIntSizeInBits(const fltSemantics &semantics,
304  bool isSigned) {
305  // The max FP value is pow(2, MaxExponent) * (1 + MaxFraction), so we need
306  // at least one more bit than the MaxExponent to hold the max FP value.
307  unsigned int MinBitWidth = semanticsMaxExponent(semantics) + 1;
308  // Extra sign bit needed.
309  if (isSigned)
310  ++MinBitWidth;
311  return MinBitWidth;
312  }

337 /* Return the value of a decimal exponent of the form
338  [+-]ddddddd.
339 
340  If the exponent overflows, returns a large exponent with the
341  appropriate sign. */
342 static Expected<int> readExponent(StringRef::iterator begin,
343  StringRef::iterator end) {
344  bool isNegative;
345  unsigned int absExponent;
346  const unsigned int overlargeExponent = 24000; /* FIXME. */
347  StringRef::iterator p = begin;
348 
349  // Treat no exponent as 0 to match binutils
350  if (p == end || ((*p == '-' || *p == '+') && (p + 1) == end)) {
351  return 0;
352  }
353 
354  isNegative = (*p == '-');
355  if (*p == '-' || *p == '+') {
356  p++;
357  if (p == end)
358  return createError("Exponent has no digits");
359  }
360 
361  absExponent = decDigitValue(*p++);
362  if (absExponent >= 10U)
363  return createError("Invalid character in exponent");
364 
365  for (; p != end; ++p) {
366  unsigned int value;
367 
368  value = decDigitValue(*p);
369  if (value >= 10U)
370  return createError("Invalid character in exponent");
371 
372  absExponent = absExponent * 10U + value;
373  if (absExponent >= overlargeExponent) {
374  absExponent = overlargeExponent;
375  break;
376  }
377  }
378 
379  if (isNegative)
380  return -(int) absExponent;
381  else
382  return (int) absExponent;
383 }

385 /* This is ugly and needs cleaning up, but I don't immediately see
386  how whilst remaining safe. */
387 static Expected<int> totalExponent(StringRef::iterator p,
388  StringRef::iterator end,
389  int exponentAdjustment) {
390  int unsignedExponent;
391  bool negative, overflow;
392  int exponent = 0;
393 
394  if (p == end)
395  return createError("Exponent has no digits");
396 
397  negative = *p == '-';
398  if (*p == '-' || *p == '+') {
399  p++;
400  if (p == end)
401  return createError("Exponent has no digits");
402  }
403 
404  unsignedExponent = 0;
405  overflow = false;
406  for (; p != end; ++p) {
407  unsigned int value;
408 
409  value = decDigitValue(*p);
410  if (value >= 10U)
411  return createError("Invalid character in exponent");
412 
413  unsignedExponent = unsignedExponent * 10 + value;
414  if (unsignedExponent > 32767) {
415  overflow = true;
416  break;
417  }
418  }
419 
420  if (exponentAdjustment > 32767 || exponentAdjustment < -32768)
421  overflow = true;
422 
423  if (!overflow) {
424  exponent = unsignedExponent;
425  if (negative)
426  exponent = -exponent;
427  exponent += exponentAdjustment;
428  if (exponent > 32767 || exponent < -32768)
429  overflow = true;
430  }
431 
432  if (overflow)
433  exponent = negative ? -32768: 32767;
434 
435  return exponent;
436 }

438 static Expected<StringRef::iterator>
439 skipLeadingZeroesAndAnyDot(StringRef::iterator begin, StringRef::iterator end,
440  StringRef::iterator *dot) {
441  StringRef::iterator p = begin;
442  *dot = end;
443  while (p != end && *p == '0')
444  p++;
445 
446  if (p != end && *p == '.') {
447  *dot = p++;
448 
449  if (end - begin == 1)
450  return createError("Significand has no digits");
451 
452  while (p != end && *p == '0')
453  p++;
454  }
455 
456  return p;
457 }

459 /* Given a normal decimal floating point number of the form
460 
461  dddd.dddd[eE][+-]ddd
462 
463  where the decimal point and exponent are optional, fill out the
464  structure D. Exponent is appropriate if the significand is
465  treated as an integer, and normalizedExponent if the significand
466  is taken to have the decimal point after a single leading
467  non-zero digit.
468 
469  If the value is zero, V->firstSigDigit points to a non-digit, and
470  the return exponent is zero.
471 */
472 struct decimalInfo {
473  const char *firstSigDigit;
474  const char *lastSigDigit;
475  int exponent;
476  int normalizedExponent;
477 };
478 
479 static Error interpretDecimal(StringRef::iterator begin,
480  StringRef::iterator end, decimalInfo *D) {
481  StringRef::iterator dot = end;
482 
483  auto PtrOrErr = skipLeadingZeroesAndAnyDot(begin, end, &dot);
484  if (!PtrOrErr)
485  return PtrOrErr.takeError();
486  StringRef::iterator p = *PtrOrErr;
487 
488  D->firstSigDigit = p;
489  D->exponent = 0;
490  D->normalizedExponent = 0;
491 
492  for (; p != end; ++p) {
493  if (*p == '.') {
494  if (dot != end)
495  return createError("String contains multiple dots");
496  dot = p++;
497  if (p == end)
498  break;
499  }
500  if (decDigitValue(*p) >= 10U)
501  break;
502  }
503 
504  if (p != end) {
505  if (*p != 'e' && *p != 'E')
506  return createError("Invalid character in significand");
507  if (p == begin)
508  return createError("Significand has no digits");
509  if (dot != end && p - begin == 1)
510  return createError("Significand has no digits");
511 
512  /* p points to the first non-digit in the string */
513  auto ExpOrErr = readExponent(p + 1, end);
514  if (!ExpOrErr)
515  return ExpOrErr.takeError();
516  D->exponent = *ExpOrErr;
517 
518  /* Implied decimal point? */
519  if (dot == end)
520  dot = p;
521  }
522 
523  /* If number is all zeroes accept any exponent. */
524  if (p != D->firstSigDigit) {
525  /* Drop insignificant trailing zeroes. */
526  if (p != begin) {
527  do
528  do
529  p--;
530  while (p != begin && *p == '0');
531  while (p != begin && *p == '.');
532  }
533 
534  /* Adjust the exponents for any decimal point. */
535  D->exponent += static_cast<APFloat::ExponentType>((dot - p) - (dot > p));
536  D->normalizedExponent = (D->exponent +
537  static_cast<APFloat::ExponentType>((p - D->firstSigDigit)
538  - (dot > D->firstSigDigit && dot < p)));
539  }
540 
541  D->lastSigDigit = p;
542  return Error::success();
543 }

545 /* Return the trailing fraction of a hexadecimal number.
546  DIGITVALUE is the first hex digit of the fraction, P points to
547  the next digit. */
548 static Expected<lostFraction>
549 trailingHexadecimalFraction(StringRef::iterator p, StringRef::iterator end,
550  unsigned int digitValue) {
551  unsigned int hexDigit;
552 
553  /* If the first trailing digit isn't 0 or 8 we can work out the
554  fraction immediately. */
555  if (digitValue > 8)
556  return lfMoreThanHalf;
557  else if (digitValue < 8 && digitValue > 0)
558  return lfLessThanHalf;
559 
560  // Otherwise we need to find the first non-zero digit.
561  while (p != end && (*p == '0' || *p == '.'))
562  p++;
563 
564  if (p == end)
565  return createError("Invalid trailing hexadecimal fraction!");
566 
567  hexDigit = hexDigitValue(*p);
568 
569  /* If we ran off the end it is exactly zero or one-half, otherwise
570  a little more. */
571  if (hexDigit == UINT_MAX)
572  return digitValue == 0 ? lfExactlyZero: lfExactlyHalf;
573  else
574  return digitValue == 0 ? lfLessThanHalf: lfMoreThanHalf;
575 }

577 /* Return the fraction lost were a bignum truncated losing the least
578  significant BITS bits. */
579 static lostFraction
580 lostFractionThroughTruncation(const APFloatBase::integerPart *parts,
581  unsigned int partCount,
582  unsigned int bits)
583 {
584  unsigned int lsb;
585 
586  lsb = APInt::tcLSB(parts, partCount);
587 
588  /* Note this is guaranteed true if bits == 0, or LSB == UINT_MAX. */
589  if (bits <= lsb)
590  return lfExactlyZero;
591  if (bits == lsb + 1)
592  return lfExactlyHalf;
593  if (bits <= partCount * APFloatBase::integerPartWidth &&
594  APInt::tcExtractBit(parts, bits - 1))
595  return lfMoreThanHalf;
596 
597  return lfLessThanHalf;
598 }

600 /* Shift DST right BITS bits noting lost fraction. */
601 static lostFraction
602 shiftRight(APFloatBase::integerPart *dst, unsigned int parts, unsigned int bits)
603 {
604  lostFraction lost_fraction;
605 
606  lost_fraction = lostFractionThroughTruncation(dst, parts, bits);
607 
608  APInt::tcShiftRight(dst, parts, bits);
609 
610  return lost_fraction;
611 }

613 /* Combine the effect of two lost fractions. */
614 static lostFraction
615 combineLostFractions(lostFraction moreSignificant,
616  lostFraction lessSignificant)
617 {
618  if (lessSignificant != lfExactlyZero) {
619  if (moreSignificant == lfExactlyZero)
620  moreSignificant = lfLessThanHalf;
621  else if (moreSignificant == lfExactlyHalf)
622  moreSignificant = lfMoreThanHalf;
623  }
624 
625  return moreSignificant;
626 }

628 /* The error from the true value, in half-ulps, on multiplying two
629  floating point numbers, which differ from the value they
630  approximate by at most HUE1 and HUE2 half-ulps, is strictly less
631  than the returned value.
632 
633  See "How to Read Floating Point Numbers Accurately" by William D
634  Clinger. */
635 static unsigned int
636 HUerrBound(bool inexactMultiply, unsigned int HUerr1, unsigned int HUerr2)
637 {
638  assert(HUerr1 < 2 || HUerr2 < 2 || (HUerr1 + HUerr2 < 8));
639 
640  if (HUerr1 + HUerr2 == 0)
641  return inexactMultiply * 2; /* <= inexactMultiply half-ulps. */
642  else
643  return inexactMultiply + 2 * (HUerr1 + HUerr2);
644 }

646 /* The number of ulps from the boundary (zero, or half if ISNEAREST)
647  when the least significant BITS are truncated. BITS cannot be
648  zero. */
649 static APFloatBase::integerPart
650 ulpsFromBoundary(const APFloatBase::integerPart *parts, unsigned int bits,
651  bool isNearest) {
652  unsigned int count, partBits;
653  APFloatBase::integerPart part, boundary;
654 
655  assert(bits != 0);
656 
657  bits--;
658  count = bits / APFloatBase::integerPartWidth;
659  partBits = bits % APFloatBase::integerPartWidth + 1;
660 
661  part = parts[count] & (~(APFloatBase::integerPart) 0 >> (APFloatBase::integerPartWidth - partBits));
662 
663  if (isNearest)
664  boundary = (APFloatBase::integerPart) 1 << (partBits - 1);
665  else
666  boundary = 0;
667 
668  if (count == 0) {
669  if (part - boundary <= boundary - part)
670  return part - boundary;
671  else
672  return boundary - part;
673  }
674 
675  if (part == boundary) {
676  while (--count)
677  if (parts[count])
678  return ~(APFloatBase::integerPart) 0; /* A lot. */
679 
680  return parts[0];
681  } else if (part == boundary - 1) {
682  while (--count)
683  if (~parts[count])
684  return ~(APFloatBase::integerPart) 0; /* A lot. */
685 
686  return -parts[0];
687  }
688 
689  return ~(APFloatBase::integerPart) 0; /* A lot. */
690 }
691 
692 /* Place pow(5, power) in DST, and return the number of parts used.
693  DST must be at least one part larger than size of the answer. */
694 static unsigned int
695 powerOf5(APFloatBase::integerPart *dst, unsigned int power) {
696  static const APFloatBase::integerPart firstEightPowers[] = { 1, 5, 25, 125, 625, 3125, 15625, 78125 };
697  APFloatBase::integerPart pow5s[maxPowerOfFiveParts * 2 + 5];
698  pow5s[0] = 78125 * 5;
699 
700  unsigned int partsCount[16] = { 1 };
701  APFloatBase::integerPart scratch[maxPowerOfFiveParts], *p1, *p2, *pow5;
702  unsigned int result;
703  assert(power <= maxExponent);
704 
705  p1 = dst;
706  p2 = scratch;
707 
708  *p1 = firstEightPowers[power & 7];
709  power >>= 3;
710 
711  result = 1;
712  pow5 = pow5s;
713 
714  for (unsigned int n = 0; power; power >>= 1, n++) {
715  unsigned int pc;
716 
717  pc = partsCount[n];
718 
719  /* Calculate pow(5,pow(2,n+3)) if we haven't yet. */
720  if (pc == 0) {
721  pc = partsCount[n - 1];
722  APInt::tcFullMultiply(pow5, pow5 - pc, pow5 - pc, pc, pc);
723  pc *= 2;
724  if (pow5[pc - 1] == 0)
725  pc--;
726  partsCount[n] = pc;
727  }
728 
729  if (power & 1) {
730  APFloatBase::integerPart *tmp;
731 
732  APInt::tcFullMultiply(p2, p1, pow5, result, pc);
733  result += pc;
734  if (p2[result - 1] == 0)
735  result--;
736 
737  /* Now result is in p1 with partsCount parts and p2 is scratch
738  space. */
739  tmp = p1;
740  p1 = p2;
741  p2 = tmp;
742  }
743 
744  pow5 += pc;
745  }
746 
747  if (p1 != dst)
748  APInt::tcAssign(dst, p1, result);
749 
750  return result;
751 }

753 /* Zero at the end to avoid modular arithmetic when adding one; used
754  when rounding up during hexadecimal output. */
755 static const char hexDigitsLower[] = "0123456789abcdef0";
756 static const char hexDigitsUpper[] = "0123456789ABCDEF0";
757 static const char infinityL[] = "infinity";
758 static const char infinityU[] = "INFINITY";
759 static const char NaNL[] = "nan";
760 static const char NaNU[] = "NAN";

762 /* Write out an integerPart in hexadecimal, starting with the most
763  significant nibble. Write out exactly COUNT hexdigits, return
764  COUNT. */
765 static unsigned int
766 partAsHex (char *dst, APFloatBase::integerPart part, unsigned int count,
767  const char *hexDigitChars)
768 {
769  unsigned int result = count;
770 
771  assert(count != 0 && count <= APFloatBase::integerPartWidth / 4);
772 
773  part >>= (APFloatBase::integerPartWidth - 4 * count);
774  while (count--) {
775  dst[count] = hexDigitChars[part & 0xf];
776  part >>= 4;
777  }
778 
779  return result;
780 }

782 /* Write out an unsigned decimal integer. */
783 static char *
784 writeUnsignedDecimal (char *dst, unsigned int n)
785 {
786  char buff[40], *p;
787 
788  p = buff;
789  do
790  *p++ = '0' + n % 10;
791  while (n /= 10);
792 
793  do
794  *dst++ = *--p;
795  while (p != buff);
796 
797  return dst;
798 }

800 /* Write out a signed decimal integer. */
801 static char *
802 writeSignedDecimal (char *dst, int value)
803 {
804  if (value < 0) {
805  *dst++ = '-';
806  dst = writeUnsignedDecimal(dst, -(unsigned) value);
807  } else
808  dst = writeUnsignedDecimal(dst, value);
809 
810  return dst;
811 }

847 /* Make this number a NaN, with an arbitrary but deterministic value
848  for the significand. If double or longer, this is a signalling NaN,
849  which may not be ideal. If float, this is QNaN(0). */
850 void IEEEFloat::makeNaN(bool SNaN, bool Negative, const APInt *fill) {
851  category = fcNaN;
852  sign = Negative;
853  exponent = exponentNaN();
854 
855  integerPart *significand = significandParts();
856  unsigned numParts = partCount();
857 
858  APInt fill_storage;
859  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly) {
860  // Finite-only types do not distinguish signalling and quiet NaN, so
861  // make them all signalling.
862  SNaN = false;
863  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero) {
864  sign = true;
865  fill_storage = APInt::getZero(semantics->precision - 1);
866  } else {
867  fill_storage = APInt::getAllOnes(semantics->precision - 1);
868  }
869  fill = &fill_storage;
870  }
871 
872  // Set the significand bits to the fill.
873  if (!fill || fill->getNumWords() < numParts)
874  APInt::tcSet(significand, 0, numParts);
875  if (fill) {
876  APInt::tcAssign(significand, fill->getRawData(),
877  std::min(fill->getNumWords(), numParts));
878 
879  // Zero out the excess bits of the significand.
880  unsigned bitsToPreserve = semantics->precision - 1;
881  unsigned part = bitsToPreserve / 64;
882  bitsToPreserve %= 64;
883  significand[part] &= ((1ULL << bitsToPreserve) - 1);
884  for (part++; part != numParts; ++part)
885  significand[part] = 0;
886  }
887 
888  unsigned QNaNBit = semantics->precision - 2;
889 
890  if (SNaN) {
891  // We always have to clear the QNaN bit to make it an SNaN.
892  APInt::tcClearBit(significand, QNaNBit);
893 
894  // If there are no bits set in the payload, we have to set
895  // *something* to make it a NaN instead of an infinity;
896  // conventionally, this is the next bit down from the QNaN bit.
897  if (APInt::tcIsZero(significand, numParts))
898  APInt::tcSetBit(significand, QNaNBit - 1);
899  } else if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero) {
900  // The only NaN is a quiet NaN, and it has no bits sets in the significand.
901  // Do nothing.
902  } else {
903  // We always have to set the QNaN bit to make it a QNaN.
904  APInt::tcSetBit(significand, QNaNBit);
905  }
906 
907  // For x87 extended precision, we want to make a NaN, not a
908  // pseudo-NaN. Maybe we should expose the ability to make
909  // pseudo-NaNs?
910  if (semantics == &semX87DoubleExtended)
911  APInt::tcSetBit(significand, QNaNBit + 1);
912 }

945 bool IEEEFloat::isSmallest() const {

947  // denormal, i.e. the floating point number with exponent being minimum

958 bool IEEEFloat::isSignificandAllOnes() const {
959  // Test if the significand excluding the integral bit is all ones. This allows
960  // us to test for binade boundaries.
961  const integerPart *Parts = significandParts();
962  const unsigned PartCount = partCountForBits(semantics->precision);
963  for (unsigned i = 0; i < PartCount - 1; i++)
964  if (~Parts[i])
965  return false;
966 
967  // Set the unused high bits to all ones when we compare.
968  const unsigned NumHighBits =
969  PartCount*integerPartWidth - semantics->precision + 1;
970  assert(NumHighBits <= integerPartWidth && NumHighBits > 0 &&
971  "Can not have more high bits to fill than integerPartWidth");
972  const integerPart HighBitFill =
973  ~integerPart(0) << (integerPartWidth - NumHighBits);
974  if (~(Parts[PartCount - 1] | HighBitFill))
975  return false;
976 
977  return true;
978 }
979 
980 bool IEEEFloat::isSignificandAllOnesExceptLSB() const {
981  // Test if the significand excluding the integral bit is all ones except for
982  // the least significant bit.
983  const integerPart *Parts = significandParts();
984 
985  if (Parts[0] & 1)
986  return false;
987 
988  const unsigned PartCount = partCountForBits(semantics->precision);
989  for (unsigned i = 0; i < PartCount - 1; i++) {
990  if (~Parts[i] & ~unsigned{!i})
991  return false;
992  }
993 
994  // Set the unused high bits to all ones when we compare.
995  const unsigned NumHighBits =
996  PartCount * integerPartWidth - semantics->precision + 1;
997  assert(NumHighBits <= integerPartWidth && NumHighBits > 0 &&
998  "Can not have more high bits to fill than integerPartWidth");
999  const integerPart HighBitFill = ~integerPart(0)
1000  << (integerPartWidth - NumHighBits);
1001  if (~(Parts[PartCount - 1] | HighBitFill | 0x1))
1002  return false;
1003 
1004  return true;
1005 }
1006 
1007 bool IEEEFloat::isSignificandAllZeros() const {
1008  // Test if the significand excluding the integral bit is all zeros. This
1009  // allows us to test for binade boundaries.
1010  const integerPart *Parts = significandParts();
1011  const unsigned PartCount = partCountForBits(semantics->precision);
1012 
1013  for (unsigned i = 0; i < PartCount - 1; i++)
1014  if (Parts[i])
1015  return false;
1016 
1017  // Compute how many bits are used in the final word.
1018  const unsigned NumHighBits =
1019  PartCount*integerPartWidth - semantics->precision + 1;
1020  assert(NumHighBits < integerPartWidth && "Can not have more high bits to "
1021  "clear than integerPartWidth");
1022  const integerPart HighBitMask = ~integerPart(0) >> NumHighBits;
1023 
1024  if (Parts[PartCount - 1] & HighBitMask)
1025  return false;
1026 
1027  return true;
1028 }

1030 bool IEEEFloat::isSignificandAllZerosExceptMSB() const {
1031  const integerPart *Parts = significandParts();
1032  const unsigned PartCount = partCountForBits(semantics->precision);
1033 
1034  for (unsigned i = 0; i < PartCount - 1; i++) {
1035  if (Parts[i])
1036  return false;
1037  }
1038 
1039  const unsigned NumHighBits =
1040  PartCount * integerPartWidth - semantics->precision + 1;
1041  return Parts[PartCount - 1] == integerPart(1)
1042  << (integerPartWidth - NumHighBits);
1043 }

1045 bool IEEEFloat::isLargest() const {
1046  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly &&
1047  semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::AllOnes) {
1048  // The largest number by magnitude in our format will be the floating point
1049  // number with maximum exponent and with significand that is all ones except
1050  // the LSB.
1051  return isFiniteNonZero() && exponent == semantics->maxExponent &&
1052  isSignificandAllOnesExceptLSB();
1053  } else {
1054  // The largest number by magnitude in our format will be the floating point
1055  // number with maximum exponent and with significand that is all ones.
1056  return isFiniteNonZero() && exponent == semantics->maxExponent &&
1057  isSignificandAllOnes();
1058  }

1069 bool IEEEFloat::bitwiseIsEqual(const IEEEFloat &rhs) const {
1070  if (this == &rhs)
1071  return true;
1072  if (semantics != rhs.semantics ||
1073  category != rhs.category ||
1074  sign != rhs.sign)

1174 /* Multiply the significand of the RHS. If ADDEND is non-NULL, add it
1175  on to the full-precision result of the multiplication. Returns the
1176  lost fraction. */
1177 lostFraction IEEEFloat::multiplySignificand(const IEEEFloat &rhs,
1178  IEEEFloat addend) {
1179  unsigned int omsb; // One, not zero, based MSB.
1180  unsigned int partsCount, newPartsCount, precision;
1181  integerPart *lhsSignificand;
1182  integerPart scratch[4];
1183  integerPart *fullSignificand;
1184  lostFraction lost_fraction;
1185  bool ignored;
1186 
1187  assert(semantics == rhs.semantics);
1188 
1189  precision = semantics->precision;
1190 
1191  // Allocate space for twice as many bits as the original significand, plus one
1192  // extra bit for the addition to overflow into.
1193  newPartsCount = partCountForBits(precision * 2 + 1);
1194 
1195  if (newPartsCount > 4)
1196  fullSignificand = new integerPart[newPartsCount];
1197  else
1198  fullSignificand = scratch;
1199 
1200  lhsSignificand = significandParts();
1201  partsCount = partCount();
1202 
1203  APInt::tcFullMultiply(fullSignificand, lhsSignificand,
1204  rhs.significandParts(), partsCount, partsCount);
1205 
1206  lost_fraction = lfExactlyZero;
1207  omsb = APInt::tcMSB(fullSignificand, newPartsCount) + 1;
1208  exponent += rhs.exponent;
1209 
1210  // Assume the operands involved in the multiplication are single-precision
1211  // FP, and the two multiplicants are:
1212  // *this = a23 . a22 ... a0 * 2^e1
1213  // rhs = b23 . b22 ... b0 * 2^e2
1214  // the result of multiplication is:
1215  // *this = c48 c47 c46 . c45 ... c0 * 2^(e1+e2)
1216  // Note that there are three significant bits at the left-hand side of the
1217  // radix point: two for the multiplication, and an overflow bit for the
1218  // addition (that will always be zero at this point). Move the radix point
1219  // toward left by two bits, and adjust exponent accordingly.
1220  exponent += 2;
1221 
1222  if (addend.isNonZero()) {
1223  // The intermediate result of the multiplication has "2 * precision"
1224  // signicant bit; adjust the addend to be consistent with mul result.
1225  //
1226  Significand savedSignificand = significand;
1227  const fltSemantics *savedSemantics = semantics;
1228  fltSemantics extendedSemantics;
1229  opStatus status;
1230  unsigned int extendedPrecision;
1231 
1232  // Normalize our MSB to one below the top bit to allow for overflow.
1233  extendedPrecision = 2 * precision + 1;
1234  if (omsb != extendedPrecision - 1) {
1235  assert(extendedPrecision > omsb);
1236  APInt::tcShiftLeft(fullSignificand, newPartsCount,
1237  (extendedPrecision - 1) - omsb);
1238  exponent -= (extendedPrecision - 1) - omsb;
1239  }
1240 
1241  /* Create new semantics. */
1242  extendedSemantics = *semantics;
1243  extendedSemantics.precision = extendedPrecision;
1244 
1245  if (newPartsCount == 1)
1246  significand.part = fullSignificand[0];
1247  else
1248  significand.parts = fullSignificand;
1249  semantics = &extendedSemantics;
1250 
1251  // Make a copy so we can convert it to the extended semantics.
1252  // Note that we cannot convert the addend directly, as the extendedSemantics
1253  // is a local variable (which we take a reference to).
1254  IEEEFloat extendedAddend(addend);
1255  status = extendedAddend.convert(extendedSemantics, rmTowardZero, &ignored);
1256  assert(status == opOK);
1257  (void)status;
1258 
1259  // Shift the significand of the addend right by one bit. This guarantees
1260  // that the high bit of the significand is zero (same as fullSignificand),
1261  // so the addition will overflow (if it does overflow at all) into the top bit.
1262  lost_fraction = extendedAddend.shiftSignificandRight(1);
1263  assert(lost_fraction == lfExactlyZero &&
1264  "Lost precision while shifting addend for fused-multiply-add.");
1265 
1266  lost_fraction = addOrSubtractSignificand(extendedAddend, false);
1267 
1268  /* Restore our state. */
1269  if (newPartsCount == 1)
1270  fullSignificand[0] = significand.part;
1271  significand = savedSignificand;
1272  semantics = savedSemantics;
1273 
1274  omsb = APInt::tcMSB(fullSignificand, newPartsCount) + 1;
1275  }
1276 
1277  // Convert the result having "2 * precision" significant-bits back to the one
1278  // having "precision" significant-bits. First, move the radix point from
1279  // poision "2*precision - 1" to "precision - 1". The exponent need to be
1280  // adjusted by "2*precision - 1" - "precision - 1" = "precision".
1281  exponent -= precision + 1;
1282 
1283  // In case MSB resides at the left-hand side of radix point, shift the
1284  // mantissa right by some amount to make sure the MSB reside right before
1285  // the radix point (i.e. "MSB . rest-significant-bits").
1286  //
1287  // Note that the result is not normalized when "omsb < precision". So, the
1288  // caller needs to call IEEEFloat::normalize() if normalized value is
1289  // expected.
1290  if (omsb > precision) {
1291  unsigned int bits, significantParts;
1292  lostFraction lf;
1293 
1294  bits = omsb - precision;
1295  significantParts = partCountForBits(omsb);
1296  lf = shiftRight(fullSignificand, significantParts, bits);
1297  lost_fraction = combineLostFractions(lf, lost_fraction);
1298  exponent += bits;
1299  }
1300 
1301  APInt::tcAssign(lhsSignificand, fullSignificand, partsCount);
1302 
1303  if (newPartsCount > 4)
1304  delete [] fullSignificand;
1305 
1306  return lost_fraction;
1307 }
1308 
1309 lostFraction IEEEFloat::multiplySignificand(const IEEEFloat &rhs) {

1313 /* Multiply the significands of LHS and RHS to DST. */
1314 lostFraction IEEEFloat::divideSignificand(const IEEEFloat &rhs) {
1315  unsigned int bit, i, partsCount;
1316  const integerPart *rhsSignificand;
1317  integerPart *lhsSignificand, *dividend, *divisor;
1318  integerPart scratch[4];
1319  lostFraction lost_fraction;
1320 
1321  assert(semantics == rhs.semantics);
1322 
1323  lhsSignificand = significandParts();
1324  rhsSignificand = rhs.significandParts();
1325  partsCount = partCount();
1326 
1327  if (partsCount > 2)
1328  dividend = new integerPart[partsCount * 2];
1329  else
1330  dividend = scratch;
1331 
1332  divisor = dividend + partsCount;
1333 
1334  /* Copy the dividend and divisor as they will be modified in-place. */
1335  for (i = 0; i < partsCount; i++) {
1336  dividend[i] = lhsSignificand[i];
1337  divisor[i] = rhsSignificand[i];
1338  lhsSignificand[i] = 0;
1339  }
1340 
1341  exponent -= rhs.exponent;
1342 
1343  unsigned int precision = semantics->precision;
1344 
1345  /* Normalize the divisor. */
1346  bit = precision - APInt::tcMSB(divisor, partsCount) - 1;
1347  if (bit) {
1348  exponent += bit;
1349  APInt::tcShiftLeft(divisor, partsCount, bit);
1350  }
1351 
1352  /* Normalize the dividend. */
1353  bit = precision - APInt::tcMSB(dividend, partsCount) - 1;
1354  if (bit) {
1355  exponent -= bit;
1356  APInt::tcShiftLeft(dividend, partsCount, bit);
1357  }
1358 
1359  /* Ensure the dividend >= divisor initially for the loop below.
1360  Incidentally, this means that the division loop below is
1361  guaranteed to set the integer bit to one. */
1362  if (APInt::tcCompare(dividend, divisor, partsCount) < 0) {
1363  exponent--;
1364  APInt::tcShiftLeft(dividend, partsCount, 1);
1365  assert(APInt::tcCompare(dividend, divisor, partsCount) >= 0);
1366  }
1367 
1368  /* Long division. */
1369  for (bit = precision; bit; bit -= 1) {
1370  if (APInt::tcCompare(dividend, divisor, partsCount) >= 0) {
1371  APInt::tcSubtract(dividend, divisor, 0, partsCount);
1372  APInt::tcSetBit(lhsSignificand, bit - 1);
1373  }
1374 
1375  APInt::tcShiftLeft(dividend, partsCount, 1);
1376  }
1377 
1378  /* Figure out the lost fraction. */
1379  int cmp = APInt::tcCompare(dividend, divisor, partsCount);
1380 
1381  if (cmp > 0)
1382  lost_fraction = lfMoreThanHalf;
1383  else if (cmp == 0)
1384  lost_fraction = lfExactlyHalf;
1385  else if (APInt::tcIsZero(dividend, partsCount))
1386  lost_fraction = lfExactlyZero;
1387  else
1388  lost_fraction = lfLessThanHalf;
1389 
1390  if (partsCount > 2)
1391  delete [] dividend;
1392 
1393  return lost_fraction;
1394 }

1404 /* Note that a zero result is NOT normalized to fcZero. */
1405 lostFraction IEEEFloat::shiftSignificandRight(unsigned int bits) {
1406  /* Our exponent should not overflow. */
1407  assert((ExponentType) (exponent + bits) >= exponent);
1408 
1409  exponent += bits;
1410 
1411  return shiftRight(significandParts(), partCount(), bits);
1412 }
1413 
1414 /* Shift the significand left BITS bits, subtract BITS from its exponent. */
1415 void IEEEFloat::shiftSignificandLeft(unsigned int bits) {
1416  assert(bits < semantics->precision);
1417 
1418  if (bits) {
1419  unsigned int partsCount = partCount();
1420 
1421  APInt::tcShiftLeft(significandParts(), partsCount, bits);
1422  exponent -= bits;
1423 
1424  assert(!APInt::tcIsZero(significandParts(), partsCount));
1425  }
1426 }

1428 IEEEFloat::cmpResult
1429 IEEEFloat::compareAbsoluteValue(const IEEEFloat &rhs) const {
1430  int compare;
1431 
1432  assert(semantics == rhs.semantics);
1433  assert(isFiniteNonZero());
1434  assert(rhs.isFiniteNonZero());
1435 
1436  compare = exponent - rhs.exponent;
1437 
1438  /* If exponents are equal, do an unsigned bignum comparison of the
1439  significands. */
1440  if (compare == 0)
1441  compare = APInt::tcCompare(significandParts(), rhs.significandParts(),
1442  partCount());
1443 
1444  if (compare > 0)
1445  return cmpGreaterThan;
1446  else if (compare < 0)
1447  return cmpLessThan;
1448  else
1449  return cmpEqual;
1450 }

1452 /* Set the least significant BITS bits of a bignum, clear the
1453  rest. */
1454 static void tcSetLeastSignificantBits(APInt::WordType *dst, unsigned parts,
1455  unsigned bits) {
1456  unsigned i = 0;
1457  while (bits > APInt::APINT_BITS_PER_WORD) {
1458  dst[i++] = ~(APInt::WordType)0;
1459  bits -= APInt::APINT_BITS_PER_WORD;
1460  }
1461 
1462  if (bits)
1463  dst[i++] = ~(APInt::WordType)0 >> (APInt::APINT_BITS_PER_WORD - bits);
1464 
1465  while (i < parts)
1466  dst[i++] = 0;
1467 }

1469 /* Handle overflow. Sign is preserved. We either become infinity or
1470  the largest finite number. */
1471 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::handleOverflow(roundingMode rounding_mode) {
1472  /* Infinity? */
1473  if (rounding_mode == rmNearestTiesToEven ||
1474  rounding_mode == rmNearestTiesToAway ||
1475  (rounding_mode == rmTowardPositive && !sign) ||
1476  (rounding_mode == rmTowardNegative && sign)) {
1477  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly)
1478  makeNaN(false, sign);
1479  else
1480  category = fcInfinity;
1481  return (opStatus) (opOverflow | opInexact);
1482  }
1483 
1484  /* Otherwise we become the largest finite number. */
1485  category = fcNormal;
1486  exponent = semantics->maxExponent;
1487  tcSetLeastSignificantBits(significandParts(), partCount(),
1488  semantics->precision);
1489  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly &&
1490  semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::AllOnes)
1491  APInt::tcClearBit(significandParts(), 0);
1492 
1493  return opInexact;
1494 }
1495 
1496 /* Returns TRUE if, when truncating the current number, with BIT the
1497  new LSB, with the given lost fraction and rounding mode, the result
1498  would need to be rounded away from zero (i.e., by increasing the
1499  signficand). This routine must work for fcZero of both signs, and
1500  fcNormal numbers. */
1501 bool IEEEFloat::roundAwayFromZero(roundingMode rounding_mode,
1502  lostFraction lost_fraction,
1503  unsigned int bit) const {
1504  /* NaNs and infinities should not have lost fractions. */
1505  assert(isFiniteNonZero() || category == fcZero);
1506 
1507  /* Current callers never pass this so we don't handle it. */
1508  assert(lost_fraction != lfExactlyZero);
1509 
1510  switch (rounding_mode) {
1511  case rmNearestTiesToAway:
1512  return lost_fraction == lfExactlyHalf || lost_fraction == lfMoreThanHalf;
1513 
1514  case rmNearestTiesToEven:
1515  if (lost_fraction == lfMoreThanHalf)
1516  return true;
1517 
1518  /* Our zeroes don't have a significand to test. */
1519  if (lost_fraction == lfExactlyHalf && category != fcZero)
1520  return APInt::tcExtractBit(significandParts(), bit);
1521 
1522  return false;
1523 
1524  case rmTowardZero:
1525  return false;
1526 
1527  case rmTowardPositive:
1528  return !sign;
1529 
1530  case rmTowardNegative:
1531  return sign;
1532 
1533  default:
1534  break;
1535  }
1536  llvm_unreachable("Invalid rounding mode found");
1537 }
1538 
1539 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::normalize(roundingMode rounding_mode,
1540  lostFraction lost_fraction) {
1541  unsigned int omsb; /* One, not zero, based MSB. */
1542  int exponentChange;
1543 
1544  if (!isFiniteNonZero())
1545  return opOK;
1546 
1547  /* Before rounding normalize the exponent of fcNormal numbers. */
1548  omsb = significandMSB() + 1;
1549 
1550  if (omsb) {
1551  /* OMSB is numbered from 1. We want to place it in the integer
1552  bit numbered PRECISION if possible, with a compensating change in
1553  the exponent. */
1554  exponentChange = omsb - semantics->precision;
1555 
1556  /* If the resulting exponent is too high, overflow according to
1557  the rounding mode. */
1558  if (exponent + exponentChange > semantics->maxExponent)
1559  return handleOverflow(rounding_mode);
1560 
1561  /* Subnormal numbers have exponent minExponent, and their MSB
1562  is forced based on that. */
1563  if (exponent + exponentChange < semantics->minExponent)
1564  exponentChange = semantics->minExponent - exponent;
1565 
1566  /* Shifting left is easy as we don't lose precision. */
1567  if (exponentChange < 0) {
1568  assert(lost_fraction == lfExactlyZero);
1569 
1570  shiftSignificandLeft(-exponentChange);
1571 
1572  return opOK;
1573  }
1574 
1575  if (exponentChange > 0) {
1576  lostFraction lf;
1577 
1578  /* Shift right and capture any new lost fraction. */
1579  lf = shiftSignificandRight(exponentChange);
1580 
1581  lost_fraction = combineLostFractions(lf, lost_fraction);
1582 
1583  /* Keep OMSB up-to-date. */
1584  if (omsb > (unsigned) exponentChange)
1585  omsb -= exponentChange;
1586  else
1587  omsb = 0;
1588  }
1589  }
1590 
1591  // The all-ones values is an overflow if NaN is all ones. If NaN is
1592  // represented by negative zero, then it is a valid finite value.
1593  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly &&
1594  semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::AllOnes &&
1595  exponent == semantics->maxExponent && isSignificandAllOnes())
1596  return handleOverflow(rounding_mode);
1597 
1598  /* Now round the number according to rounding_mode given the lost
1599  fraction. */
1600 
1601  /* As specified in IEEE 754, since we do not trap we do not report
1602  underflow for exact results. */
1603  if (lost_fraction == lfExactlyZero) {
1604  /* Canonicalize zeroes. */
1605  if (omsb == 0) {
1606  category = fcZero;
1607  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
1608  sign = false;
1609  }
1610 
1611  return opOK;
1612  }
1613 
1614  /* Increment the significand if we're rounding away from zero. */
1615  if (roundAwayFromZero(rounding_mode, lost_fraction, 0)) {
1616  if (omsb == 0)
1617  exponent = semantics->minExponent;
1618 
1619  incrementSignificand();
1620  omsb = significandMSB() + 1;
1621 
1622  /* Did the significand increment overflow? */
1623  if (omsb == (unsigned) semantics->precision + 1) {
1624  /* Renormalize by incrementing the exponent and shifting our
1625  significand right one. However if we already have the
1626  maximum exponent we overflow to infinity. */
1627  if (exponent == semantics->maxExponent)
1628  // Invoke overflow handling with a rounding mode that will guarantee
1629  // that the result gets turned into the correct infinity representation.
1630  // This is needed instead of just setting the category to infinity to
1631  // account for 8-bit floating point types that have no inf, only NaN.
1632  return handleOverflow(sign ? rmTowardNegative : rmTowardPositive);
1633 
1634  shiftSignificandRight(1);
1635 
1636  return opInexact;
1637  }
1638 
1639  // The all-ones values is an overflow if NaN is all ones. If NaN is
1640  // represented by negative zero, then it is a valid finite value.
1641  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly &&
1642  semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::AllOnes &&
1643  exponent == semantics->maxExponent && isSignificandAllOnes())
1644  return handleOverflow(rounding_mode);
1645  }
1646 
1647  /* The normal case - we were and are not denormal, and any
1648  significand increment above didn't overflow. */
1649  if (omsb == semantics->precision)
1650  return opInexact;
1651 
1652  /* We have a non-zero denormal. */
1653  assert(omsb < semantics->precision);
1654 
1655  /* Canonicalize zeroes. */
1656  if (omsb == 0) {
1657  category = fcZero;
1658  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
1659  sign = false;
1660  }
1661 
1662  /* The fcZero case is a denormal that underflowed to zero. */
1663  return (opStatus) (opUnderflow | opInexact);
1664 }

1666 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::addOrSubtractSpecials(const IEEEFloat &rhs,
1667  bool subtract) {
1668  switch (PackCategoriesIntoKey(category, rhs.category)) {
1669  default:
1670  llvm_unreachable(nullptr);
1671 
1672  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcNaN):
1673  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcNaN):
1674  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcNaN):
1675  assign(rhs);
1676  [[fallthrough]];
1677  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcZero):
1678  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcNormal):
1679  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcInfinity):
1680  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcNaN):
1681  if (isSignaling()) {
1682  makeQuiet();
1683  return opInvalidOp;
1684  }
1685  return rhs.isSignaling() ? opInvalidOp : opOK;
1686 
1687  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcZero):
1688  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcNormal):
1689  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcZero):
1690  return opOK;
1691 
1692  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcInfinity):
1693  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcInfinity):
1694  category = fcInfinity;
1695  sign = rhs.sign ^ subtract;
1696  return opOK;
1697 
1698  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcNormal):
1699  assign(rhs);
1700  sign = rhs.sign ^ subtract;
1701  return opOK;
1702 
1703  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcZero):
1704  /* Sign depends on rounding mode; handled by caller. */
1705  return opOK;
1706 
1707  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcInfinity):
1708  /* Differently signed infinities can only be validly
1709  subtracted. */
1710  if (((sign ^ rhs.sign)!=0) != subtract) {
1711  makeNaN();
1712  return opInvalidOp;
1713  }
1714 
1715  return opOK;
1716 
1717  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcNormal):
1718  return opDivByZero;
1719  }
1720 }

1722 /* Add or subtract two normal numbers. */
1723 lostFraction IEEEFloat::addOrSubtractSignificand(const IEEEFloat &rhs,
1724  bool subtract) {
1725  integerPart carry;
1726  lostFraction lost_fraction;
1727  int bits;
1728 
1729  /* Determine if the operation on the absolute values is effectively
1730  an addition or subtraction. */
1731  subtract ^= static_cast<bool>(sign ^ rhs.sign);
1732 
1733  /* Are we bigger exponent-wise than the RHS? */
1734  bits = exponent - rhs.exponent;
1735 
1736  /* Subtraction is more subtle than one might naively expect. */
1737  if (subtract) {
1738  IEEEFloat temp_rhs(rhs);
1739 
1740  if (bits == 0)
1741  lost_fraction = lfExactlyZero;
1742  else if (bits > 0) {
1743  lost_fraction = temp_rhs.shiftSignificandRight(bits - 1);
1744  shiftSignificandLeft(1);
1745  } else {
1746  lost_fraction = shiftSignificandRight(-bits - 1);
1747  temp_rhs.shiftSignificandLeft(1);
1748  }
1749 
1750  // Should we reverse the subtraction.
1751  if (compareAbsoluteValue(temp_rhs) == cmpLessThan) {
1752  carry = temp_rhs.subtractSignificand
1753  (*this, lost_fraction != lfExactlyZero);
1754  copySignificand(temp_rhs);
1755  sign = !sign;
1756  } else {
1757  carry = subtractSignificand
1758  (temp_rhs, lost_fraction != lfExactlyZero);
1759  }
1760 
1761  /* Invert the lost fraction - it was on the RHS and
1762  subtracted. */
1763  if (lost_fraction == lfLessThanHalf)
1764  lost_fraction = lfMoreThanHalf;
1765  else if (lost_fraction == lfMoreThanHalf)
1766  lost_fraction = lfLessThanHalf;
1767 
1768  /* The code above is intended to ensure that no borrow is
1769  necessary. */
1770  assert(!carry);
1771  (void)carry;
1772  } else {
1773  if (bits > 0) {
1774  IEEEFloat temp_rhs(rhs);
1775 
1776  lost_fraction = temp_rhs.shiftSignificandRight(bits);
1777  carry = addSignificand(temp_rhs);
1778  } else {
1779  lost_fraction = shiftSignificandRight(-bits);
1780  carry = addSignificand(rhs);
1781  }
1782 
1783  /* We have a guard bit; generating a carry cannot happen. */
1784  assert(!carry);
1785  (void)carry;
1786  }
1787 
1788  return lost_fraction;
1789 }

1953  return opInvalidOp;
1954 
1955  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcNormal):
1956  return opDivByZero; // fake status, indicating this is not a special case
1957  }
1958 }
1959 
1960 /* Change sign. */
1961 void IEEEFloat::changeSign() {
1962  // With NaN-as-negative-zero, neither NaN or negative zero can change
1963  // their signs.
1964  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero &&
1965  (isZero() || isNaN()))
1966  return;
1967  /* Look mummy, this one's easy. */
1968  sign = !sign;
1969 }

1971 /* Normalized addition or subtraction. */
1972 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::addOrSubtract(const IEEEFloat &rhs,
1973  roundingMode rounding_mode,
1974  bool subtract) {
1975  opStatus fs;
1976 
1977  fs = addOrSubtractSpecials(rhs, subtract);
1978 
1979  /* This return code means it was not a simple case. */
1980  if (fs == opDivByZero) {
1981  lostFraction lost_fraction;
1982 
1983  lost_fraction = addOrSubtractSignificand(rhs, subtract);
1984  fs = normalize(rounding_mode, lost_fraction);
1985 
1986  /* Can only be zero if we lost no fraction. */
1987  assert(category != fcZero || lost_fraction == lfExactlyZero);
1988  }
1989 
1990  /* If two numbers add (exactly) to zero, IEEE 754 decrees it is a
1991  positive zero unless rounding to minus infinity, except that
1992  adding two like-signed zeroes gives that zero. */
1993  if (category == fcZero) {
1994  if (rhs.category != fcZero || (sign == rhs.sign) == subtract)
1995  sign = (rounding_mode == rmTowardNegative);
1996  // NaN-in-negative-zero means zeros need to be normalized to +0.
1997  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
1998  sign = false;
1999  }
2000 
2001  return fs;
2002 }
2003

2005 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::add(const IEEEFloat &rhs,
2006  roundingMode rounding_mode) {
2007  return addOrSubtract(rhs, rounding_mode, false);
2008 }

2012  roundingMode rounding_mode) {
2013  return addOrSubtract(rhs, rounding_mode, true);
2014 }

2030  fs = (opStatus) (fs | opInexact);
2031  }
2032 
2033  return fs;

2056 /* Normalized remainder. */
2057 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::remainder(const IEEEFloat &rhs) {
2058  opStatus fs;
2059  unsigned int origSign = sign;
2060 
2061  // First handle the special cases.
2062  fs = remainderSpecials(rhs);
2063  if (fs != opDivByZero)
2064  return fs;
2065 
2066  fs = opOK;
2067 
2068  // Make sure the current value is less than twice the denom. If the addition
2069  // did not succeed (an overflow has happened), which means that the finite
2070  // value we currently posses must be less than twice the denom (as we are
2071  // using the same semantics).
2072  IEEEFloat P2 = rhs;
2073  if (P2.add(rhs, rmNearestTiesToEven) == opOK) {
2074  fs = mod(P2);
2075  assert(fs == opOK);
2076  }
2077 
2078  // Lets work with absolute numbers.
2079  IEEEFloat P = rhs;
2080  P.sign = false;
2081  sign = false;
2082 
2083  //
2084  // To calculate the remainder we use the following scheme.
2085  //
2086  // The remainder is defained as follows:
2087  //
2088  // remainder = numer - rquot * denom = x - r * p
2089  //
2090  // Where r is the result of: x/p, rounded toward the nearest integral value
2091  // (with halfway cases rounded toward the even number).
2092  //
2093  // Currently, (after x mod 2p):
2094  // r is the number of 2p's present inside x, which is inherently, an even
2095  // number of p's.
2096  //
2097  // We may split the remaining calculation into 4 options:
2098  // - if x < 0.5p then we round to the nearest number with is 0, and are done.
2099  // - if x == 0.5p then we round to the nearest even number which is 0, and we
2100  // are done as well.
2101  // - if 0.5p < x < p then we round to nearest number which is 1, and we have
2102  // to subtract 1p at least once.
2103  // - if x >= p then we must subtract p at least once, as x must be a
2104  // remainder.
2105  //
2106  // By now, we were done, or we added 1 to r, which in turn, now an odd number.
2107  //
2108  // We can now split the remaining calculation to the following 3 options:
2109  // - if x < 0.5p then we round to the nearest number with is 0, and are done.
2110  // - if x == 0.5p then we round to the nearest even number. As r is odd, we
2111  // must round up to the next even number. so we must subtract p once more.
2112  // - if x > 0.5p (and inherently x < p) then we must round r up to the next
2113  // integral, and subtract p once more.
2114  //
2115 
2116  // Extend the semantics to prevent an overflow/underflow or inexact result.
2117  bool losesInfo;
2118  fltSemantics extendedSemantics = *semantics;
2119  extendedSemantics.maxExponent++;
2120  extendedSemantics.minExponent--;
2121  extendedSemantics.precision += 2;
2122 
2123  IEEEFloat VEx = *this;
2124  fs = VEx.convert(extendedSemantics, rmNearestTiesToEven, &losesInfo);
2125  assert(fs == opOK && !losesInfo);
2126  IEEEFloat PEx = P;
2127  fs = PEx.convert(extendedSemantics, rmNearestTiesToEven, &losesInfo);
2128  assert(fs == opOK && !losesInfo);
2129 
2130  // It is simpler to work with 2x instead of 0.5p, and we do not need to lose
2131  // any fraction.
2132  fs = VEx.add(VEx, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2133  assert(fs == opOK);
2134 
2135  if (VEx.compare(PEx) == cmpGreaterThan) {
2136  fs = subtract(P, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2137  assert(fs == opOK);
2138 
2139  // Make VEx = this.add(this), but because we have different semantics, we do
2140  // not want to `convert` again, so we just subtract PEx twice (which equals
2141  // to the desired value).
2142  fs = VEx.subtract(PEx, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2143  assert(fs == opOK);
2144  fs = VEx.subtract(PEx, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2145  assert(fs == opOK);
2146 
2147  cmpResult result = VEx.compare(PEx);
2148  if (result == cmpGreaterThan || result == cmpEqual) {
2149  fs = subtract(P, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2150  assert(fs == opOK);
2151  }
2152  }
2153 
2154  if (isZero()) {
2155  sign = origSign; // IEEE754 requires this
2156  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
2157  // But some 8-bit floats only have positive 0.
2158  sign = false;
2159  }
2160 
2161  else
2162  sign ^= origSign;
2163  return fs;
2164 }
2165 
2166 /* Normalized llvm frem (C fmod). */
2167 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::mod(const IEEEFloat &rhs) {
2168  opStatus fs;
2169  fs = modSpecials(rhs);
2170  unsigned int origSign = sign;
2171 
2172  while (isFiniteNonZero() && rhs.isFiniteNonZero() &&
2173  compareAbsoluteValue(rhs) != cmpLessThan) {
2174  int Exp = ilogb(*this) - ilogb(rhs);
2175  IEEEFloat V = scalbn(rhs, Exp, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2176  // V can overflow to NaN with fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly, so explicitly
2177  // check for it.
2178  if (V.isNaN() || compareAbsoluteValue(V) == cmpLessThan)
2179  V = scalbn(rhs, Exp - 1, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2180  V.sign = sign;
2181 
2182  fs = subtract(V, rmNearestTiesToEven);
2183  assert(fs==opOK);
2184  }
2185  if (isZero()) {
2186  sign = origSign; // fmod requires this
2187  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
2188  sign = false;
2189  }
2190  return fs;
2191 }

2193 /* Normalized fused-multiply-add. */
2194 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::fusedMultiplyAdd(const IEEEFloat &multiplicand,
2195  const IEEEFloat &addend,
2196  roundingMode rounding_mode) {
2197  opStatus fs;
2198 
2199  /* Post-multiplication sign, before addition. */
2200  sign ^= multiplicand.sign;
2201 
2202  /* If and only if all arguments are normal do we need to do an
2203  extended-precision calculation. */
2204  if (isFiniteNonZero() &&
2205  multiplicand.isFiniteNonZero() &&
2206  addend.isFinite()) {
2207  lostFraction lost_fraction;
2208 
2209  lost_fraction = multiplySignificand(multiplicand, addend);
2210  fs = normalize(rounding_mode, lost_fraction);
2211  if (lost_fraction != lfExactlyZero)
2212  fs = (opStatus) (fs | opInexact);
2213 
2214  /* If two numbers add (exactly) to zero, IEEE 754 decrees it is a
2215  positive zero unless rounding to minus infinity, except that
2216  adding two like-signed zeroes gives that zero. */
2217  if (category == fcZero && !(fs & opUnderflow) && sign != addend.sign) {
2218  sign = (rounding_mode == rmTowardNegative);
2219  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
2220  sign = false;
2221  }
2222  } else {
2223  fs = multiplySpecials(multiplicand);
2224 
2225  /* FS can only be opOK or opInvalidOp. There is no more work
2226  to do in the latter case. The IEEE-754R standard says it is
2227  implementation-defined in this case whether, if ADDEND is a
2228  quiet NaN, we raise invalid op; this implementation does so.
2229 
2230  If we need to do the addition we can do so with normal
2231  precision. */
2232  if (fs == opOK)
2233  fs = addOrSubtract(addend, rounding_mode, false);
2234  }
2235 
2236  return fs;
2237 }

2239 /* Rounding-mode correct round to integral value. */
2240 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::roundToIntegral(roundingMode rounding_mode) {
2241  opStatus fs;
2242 
2243  if (isInfinity())
2244  // [IEEE Std 754-2008 6.1]:
2245  // The behavior of infinity in floating-point arithmetic is derived from the
2246  // limiting cases of real arithmetic with operands of arbitrarily
2247  // large magnitude, when such a limit exists.
2248  // ...
2249  // Operations on infinite operands are usually exact and therefore signal no
2250  // exceptions ...
2251  return opOK;
2252 
2253  if (isNaN()) {
2254  if (isSignaling()) {
2255  // [IEEE Std 754-2008 6.2]:
2256  // Under default exception handling, any operation signaling an invalid
2257  // operation exception and for which a floating-point result is to be
2258  // delivered shall deliver a quiet NaN.
2259  makeQuiet();
2260  // [IEEE Std 754-2008 6.2]:
2261  // Signaling NaNs shall be reserved operands that, under default exception
2262  // handling, signal the invalid operation exception(see 7.2) for every
2263  // general-computational and signaling-computational operation except for
2264  // the conversions described in 5.12.
2265  return opInvalidOp;
2266  } else {
2267  // [IEEE Std 754-2008 6.2]:
2268  // For an operation with quiet NaN inputs, other than maximum and minimum
2269  // operations, if a floating-point result is to be delivered the result
2270  // shall be a quiet NaN which should be one of the input NaNs.
2271  // ...
2272  // Every general-computational and quiet-computational operation involving
2273  // one or more input NaNs, none of them signaling, shall signal no
2274  // exception, except fusedMultiplyAdd might signal the invalid operation
2275  // exception(see 7.2).
2276  return opOK;
2277  }
2278  }
2279 
2280  if (isZero()) {
2281  // [IEEE Std 754-2008 6.3]:
2282  // ... the sign of the result of conversions, the quantize operation, the
2283  // roundToIntegral operations, and the roundToIntegralExact(see 5.3.1) is
2284  // the sign of the first or only operand.
2285  return opOK;
2286  }
2287 
2288  // If the exponent is large enough, we know that this value is already
2289  // integral, and the arithmetic below would potentially cause it to saturate
2290  // to +/-Inf. Bail out early instead.
2291  if (exponent+1 >= (int)semanticsPrecision(*semantics))
2292  return opOK;
2293 
2294  // The algorithm here is quite simple: we add 2^(p-1), where p is the
2295  // precision of our format, and then subtract it back off again. The choice
2296  // of rounding modes for the addition/subtraction determines the rounding mode
2297  // for our integral rounding as well.
2298  // NOTE: When the input value is negative, we do subtraction followed by
2299  // addition instead.
2300  APInt IntegerConstant(NextPowerOf2(semanticsPrecision(*semantics)), 1);
2301  IntegerConstant <<= semanticsPrecision(*semantics)-1;
2302  IEEEFloat MagicConstant(*semantics);
2303  fs = MagicConstant.convertFromAPInt(IntegerConstant, false,
2304  rmNearestTiesToEven);
2305  assert(fs == opOK);
2306  MagicConstant.sign = sign;
2307 
2308  // Preserve the input sign so that we can handle the case of zero result
2309  // correctly.
2310  bool inputSign = isNegative();
2311 
2312  fs = add(MagicConstant, rounding_mode);
2313 
2314  // Current value and 'MagicConstant' are both integers, so the result of the
2315  // subtraction is always exact according to Sterbenz' lemma.
2316  subtract(MagicConstant, rounding_mode);
2317 
2318  // Restore the input sign.
2319  if (inputSign != isNegative())
2320  changeSign();
2321 
2322  return fs;
2323 }

2325 
2326 /* Comparison requires normalized numbers. */
2327 IEEEFloat::cmpResult IEEEFloat::compare(const IEEEFloat &rhs) const {
2328  cmpResult result;
2329 
2330  assert(semantics == rhs.semantics);
2331 
2332  switch (PackCategoriesIntoKey(category, rhs.category)) {
2333  default:
2334  llvm_unreachable(nullptr);
2335 
2336  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcZero):
2337  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcNormal):
2338  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcInfinity):
2339  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNaN, fcNaN):
2340  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcNaN):
2341  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcNaN):
2342  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcNaN):
2343  return cmpUnordered;
2344 
2345  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcNormal):
2346  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcZero):
2347  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcZero):
2348  if (sign)
2349  return cmpLessThan;
2350  else
2351  return cmpGreaterThan;
2352 
2353  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcInfinity):
2354  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcInfinity):
2355  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcNormal):
2356  if (rhs.sign)
2357  return cmpGreaterThan;
2358  else
2359  return cmpLessThan;
2360 
2361  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcInfinity, fcInfinity):
2362  if (sign == rhs.sign)
2363  return cmpEqual;
2364  else if (sign)
2365  return cmpLessThan;
2366  else
2367  return cmpGreaterThan;
2368 
2369  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcZero, fcZero):
2370  return cmpEqual;
2371 
2372  case PackCategoriesIntoKey(fcNormal, fcNormal):
2373  break;
2374  }
2375 
2376  /* Two normal numbers. Do they have the same sign? */
2377  if (sign != rhs.sign) {
2378  if (sign)
2379  result = cmpLessThan;
2380  else
2381  result = cmpGreaterThan;
2382  } else {
2383  /* Compare absolute values; invert result if negative. */
2384  result = compareAbsoluteValue(rhs);
2385 
2386  if (sign) {
2387  if (result == cmpLessThan)
2388  result = cmpGreaterThan;
2389  else if (result == cmpGreaterThan)
2390  result = cmpLessThan;
2391  }
2392  }
2393 
2394  return result;
2395 }

2397 /// IEEEFloat::convert - convert a value of one floating point type to another.
2398 /// The return value corresponds to the IEEE754 exceptions. *losesInfo
2399 /// records whether the transformation lost information, i.e. whether
2400 /// converting the result back to the original type will produce the
2401 /// original value (this is almost the same as return value==fsOK, but there
2402 /// are edge cases where this is not so).
2403 
2404 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::convert(const fltSemantics &toSemantics,
2405  roundingMode rounding_mode,
2406  bool *losesInfo) {
2407  lostFraction lostFraction;
2408  unsigned int newPartCount, oldPartCount;
2409  opStatus fs;
2410  int shift;
2411  const fltSemantics &fromSemantics = *semantics;
2412  bool is_signaling = isSignaling();
2413 
2414  lostFraction = lfExactlyZero;
2415  newPartCount = partCountForBits(toSemantics.precision + 1);
2416  oldPartCount = partCount();
2417  shift = toSemantics.precision - fromSemantics.precision;
2418 
2419  bool X86SpecialNan = false;
2420  if (&fromSemantics == &semX87DoubleExtended &&
2421  &toSemantics != &semX87DoubleExtended && category == fcNaN &&
2422  (!(*significandParts() & 0x8000000000000000ULL) ||
2423  !(*significandParts() & 0x4000000000000000ULL))) {
2424  // x86 has some unusual NaNs which cannot be represented in any other
2425  // format; note them here.
2426  X86SpecialNan = true;
2427  }
2428 
2429  // If this is a truncation of a denormal number, and the target semantics
2430  // has larger exponent range than the source semantics (this can happen
2431  // when truncating from PowerPC double-double to double format), the
2432  // right shift could lose result mantissa bits. Adjust exponent instead
2433  // of performing excessive shift.
2434  // Also do a similar trick in case shifting denormal would produce zero
2435  // significand as this case isn't handled correctly by normalize.
2436  if (shift < 0 && isFiniteNonZero()) {
2437  int omsb = significandMSB() + 1;
2438  int exponentChange = omsb - fromSemantics.precision;
2439  if (exponent + exponentChange < toSemantics.minExponent)
2440  exponentChange = toSemantics.minExponent - exponent;
2441  if (exponentChange < shift)
2442  exponentChange = shift;
2443  if (exponentChange < 0) {
2444  shift -= exponentChange;
2445  exponent += exponentChange;
2446  } else if (omsb <= -shift) {
2447  exponentChange = omsb + shift - 1; // leave at least one bit set
2448  shift -= exponentChange;
2449  exponent += exponentChange;
2450  }
2451  }
2452 
2453  // If this is a truncation, perform the shift before we narrow the storage.
2454  if (shift < 0 && (isFiniteNonZero() ||
2455  (category == fcNaN && semantics->nonFiniteBehavior !=
2456  fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly)))
2457  lostFraction = shiftRight(significandParts(), oldPartCount, -shift);
2458 
2459  // Fix the storage so it can hold to new value.
2460  if (newPartCount > oldPartCount) {
2461  // The new type requires more storage; make it available.
2462  integerPart *newParts;
2463  newParts = new integerPart[newPartCount];
2464  APInt::tcSet(newParts, 0, newPartCount);
2465  if (isFiniteNonZero() || category==fcNaN)
2466  APInt::tcAssign(newParts, significandParts(), oldPartCount);
2467  freeSignificand();
2468  significand.parts = newParts;
2469  } else if (newPartCount == 1 && oldPartCount != 1) {
2470  // Switch to built-in storage for a single part.
2471  integerPart newPart = 0;
2472  if (isFiniteNonZero() || category==fcNaN)
2473  newPart = significandParts()[0];
2474  freeSignificand();
2475  significand.part = newPart;
2476  }
2477 
2478  // Now that we have the right storage, switch the semantics.
2479  semantics = &toSemantics;
2480 
2481  // If this is an extension, perform the shift now that the storage is
2482  // available.
2483  if (shift > 0 && (isFiniteNonZero() || category==fcNaN))
2484  APInt::tcShiftLeft(significandParts(), newPartCount, shift);
2485 
2486  if (isFiniteNonZero()) {
2487  fs = normalize(rounding_mode, lostFraction);
2488  *losesInfo = (fs != opOK);
2489  } else if (category == fcNaN) {
2490  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly) {
2491  *losesInfo =
2492  fromSemantics.nonFiniteBehavior != fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly;
2493  makeNaN(false, sign);
2494  return is_signaling ? opInvalidOp : opOK;
2495  }
2496 
2497  // If NaN is negative zero, we need to create a new NaN to avoid converting
2498  // NaN to -Inf.
2499  if (fromSemantics.nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero &&
2500  semantics->nanEncoding != fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
2501  makeNaN(false, false);
2502 
2503  *losesInfo = lostFraction != lfExactlyZero || X86SpecialNan;
2504 
2505  // For x87 extended precision, we want to make a NaN, not a special NaN if
2506  // the input wasn't special either.
2507  if (!X86SpecialNan && semantics == &semX87DoubleExtended)
2508  APInt::tcSetBit(significandParts(), semantics->precision - 1);
2509 
2510  // Convert of sNaN creates qNaN and raises an exception (invalid op).
2511  // This also guarantees that a sNaN does not become Inf on a truncation
2512  // that loses all payload bits.
2513  if (is_signaling) {
2514  makeQuiet();
2515  fs = opInvalidOp;
2516  } else {
2517  fs = opOK;
2518  }
2519  } else if (category == fcInfinity &&
2520  semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly) {
2521  makeNaN(false, sign);
2522  *losesInfo = true;
2523  fs = opInexact;
2524  } else if (category == fcZero &&
2525  semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero) {
2526  // Negative zero loses info, but positive zero doesn't.
2527  *losesInfo =
2528  fromSemantics.nanEncoding != fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero && sign;
2529  fs = *losesInfo ? opInexact : opOK;
2530  // NaN is negative zero means -0 -> +0, which can lose information
2531  sign = false;
2532  } else {
2533  *losesInfo = false;
2534  fs = opOK;
2535  }
2536 
2537  return fs;
2538 }
2539 
2540 /* Convert a floating point number to an integer according to the
2541  rounding mode. If the rounded integer value is out of range this
2542  returns an invalid operation exception and the contents of the
2543  destination parts are unspecified. If the rounded value is in
2544  range but the floating point number is not the exact integer, the C
2545  standard doesn't require an inexact exception to be raised. IEEE
2546  854 does require it so we do that.
2547 
2548  Note that for conversions to integer type the C standard requires
2549  round-to-zero to always be used. */
2550 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::convertToSignExtendedInteger(
2551  MutableArrayRef<integerPart> parts, unsigned int width, bool isSigned,
2552  roundingMode rounding_mode, bool *isExact) const {
2553  lostFraction lost_fraction;
2554  const integerPart *src;
2555  unsigned int dstPartsCount, truncatedBits;
2556 
2557  *isExact = false;
2558 
2559  /* Handle the three special cases first. */
2560  if (category == fcInfinity || category == fcNaN)
2561  return opInvalidOp;
2562 
2563  dstPartsCount = partCountForBits(width);
2564  assert(dstPartsCount <= parts.size() && "Integer too big");
2565 
2566  if (category == fcZero) {
2567  APInt::tcSet(parts.data(), 0, dstPartsCount);
2568  // Negative zero can't be represented as an int.
2569  *isExact = !sign;
2570  return opOK;
2571  }
2572 
2573  src = significandParts();
2574 
2575  /* Step 1: place our absolute value, with any fraction truncated, in
2576  the destination. */
2577  if (exponent < 0) {
2578  /* Our absolute value is less than one; truncate everything. */
2579  APInt::tcSet(parts.data(), 0, dstPartsCount);
2580  /* For exponent -1 the integer bit represents .5, look at that.
2581  For smaller exponents leftmost truncated bit is 0. */
2582  truncatedBits = semantics->precision -1U - exponent;
2583  } else {
2584  /* We want the most significant (exponent + 1) bits; the rest are
2585  truncated. */
2586  unsigned int bits = exponent + 1U;
2587 
2588  /* Hopelessly large in magnitude? */
2589  if (bits > width)
2590  return opInvalidOp;
2591 
2592  if (bits < semantics->precision) {
2593  /* We truncate (semantics->precision - bits) bits. */
2594  truncatedBits = semantics->precision - bits;
2595  APInt::tcExtract(parts.data(), dstPartsCount, src, bits, truncatedBits);
2596  } else {
2597  /* We want at least as many bits as are available. */
2598  APInt::tcExtract(parts.data(), dstPartsCount, src, semantics->precision,
2599  0);
2600  APInt::tcShiftLeft(parts.data(), dstPartsCount,
2601  bits - semantics->precision);
2602  truncatedBits = 0;
2603  }
2604  }
2605 
2606  /* Step 2: work out any lost fraction, and increment the absolute
2607  value if we would round away from zero. */
2608  if (truncatedBits) {
2609  lost_fraction = lostFractionThroughTruncation(src, partCount(),
2610  truncatedBits);
2611  if (lost_fraction != lfExactlyZero &&
2612  roundAwayFromZero(rounding_mode, lost_fraction, truncatedBits)) {
2613  if (APInt::tcIncrement(parts.data(), dstPartsCount))
2614  return opInvalidOp; /* Overflow. */
2615  }
2616  } else {
2617  lost_fraction = lfExactlyZero;
2618  }
2619 
2620  /* Step 3: check if we fit in the destination. */
2621  unsigned int omsb = APInt::tcMSB(parts.data(), dstPartsCount) + 1;
2622 
2623  if (sign) {
2624  if (!isSigned) {
2625  /* Negative numbers cannot be represented as unsigned. */
2626  if (omsb != 0)
2627  return opInvalidOp;
2628  } else {
2629  /* It takes omsb bits to represent the unsigned integer value.
2630  We lose a bit for the sign, but care is needed as the
2631  maximally negative integer is a special case. */
2632  if (omsb == width &&
2633  APInt::tcLSB(parts.data(), dstPartsCount) + 1 != omsb)
2634  return opInvalidOp;
2635 
2636  /* This case can happen because of rounding. */
2637  if (omsb > width)
2638  return opInvalidOp;
2639  }
2640 
2641  APInt::tcNegate (parts.data(), dstPartsCount);
2642  } else {
2643  if (omsb >= width + !isSigned)
2644  return opInvalidOp;
2645  }
2646 
2647  if (lost_fraction == lfExactlyZero) {
2648  *isExact = true;
2649  return opOK;
2650  } else
2651  return opInexact;
2652 }
2653 
2654 /* Same as convertToSignExtendedInteger, except we provide
2655  deterministic values in case of an invalid operation exception,
2656  namely zero for NaNs and the minimal or maximal value respectively
2657  for underflow or overflow.
2658  The *isExact output tells whether the result is exact, in the sense
2659  that converting it back to the original floating point type produces
2660  the original value. This is almost equivalent to result==opOK,
2661  except for negative zeroes.
2662 */
2663 IEEEFloat::opStatus
2664 IEEEFloat::convertToInteger(MutableArrayRef<integerPart> parts,
2665  unsigned int width, bool isSigned,
2666  roundingMode rounding_mode, bool *isExact) const {
2667  opStatus fs;
2668 
2669  fs = convertToSignExtendedInteger(parts, width, isSigned, rounding_mode,
2670  isExact);
2671 
2672  if (fs == opInvalidOp) {
2673  unsigned int bits, dstPartsCount;
2674 
2675  dstPartsCount = partCountForBits(width);
2676  assert(dstPartsCount <= parts.size() && "Integer too big");
2677 
2678  if (category == fcNaN)
2679  bits = 0;
2680  else if (sign)
2681  bits = isSigned;
2682  else
2683  bits = width - isSigned;
2684 
2685  tcSetLeastSignificantBits(parts.data(), dstPartsCount, bits);
2686  if (sign && isSigned)
2687  APInt::tcShiftLeft(parts.data(), dstPartsCount, width - 1);
2688  }
2689 
2690  return fs;
2691 }

2694  rounding according to ROUNDING_MODE. The sign of the floating
2695  point number is not modified. */
2696 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::convertFromUnsignedParts(
2697  const integerPart *src, unsigned int srcCount, roundingMode rounding_mode) {

2699  integerPart *dst;
2700  lostFraction lost_fraction;
2701 
2702  category = fcNormal;
2703  omsb = APInt::tcMSB(src, srcCount) + 1;
2704  dst = significandParts();
2705  dstCount = partCount();

2707

2709  be that many; extract what we can. */

2711  exponent = omsb - 1;

2717  lost_fraction = lfExactlyZero;
2718  APInt::tcExtract(dst, dstCount, src, omsb, 0);
2719  }
2720

2783 Expected<IEEEFloat::opStatus>
2784 IEEEFloat::convertFromHexadecimalString(StringRef s,
2785  roundingMode rounding_mode) {
2786  lostFraction lost_fraction = lfExactlyZero;
2787 
2788  category = fcNormal;
2789  zeroSignificand();
2790  exponent = 0;
2791 
2792  integerPart *significand = significandParts();
2793  unsigned partsCount = partCount();
2794  unsigned bitPos = partsCount * integerPartWidth;
2795  bool computedTrailingFraction = false;
2796 
2797  // Skip leading zeroes and any (hexa)decimal point.
2798  StringRef::iterator begin = s.begin();
2799  StringRef::iterator end = s.end();
2800  StringRef::iterator dot;
2801  auto PtrOrErr = skipLeadingZeroesAndAnyDot(begin, end, &dot);
2802  if (!PtrOrErr)
2803  return PtrOrErr.takeError();
2804  StringRef::iterator p = *PtrOrErr;
2805  StringRef::iterator firstSignificantDigit = p;
2806 
2807  while (p != end) {
2808  integerPart hex_value;
2809 
2810  if (*p == '.') {
2811  if (dot != end)
2812  return createError("String contains multiple dots");
2813  dot = p++;
2814  continue;
2815  }
2816 
2817  hex_value = hexDigitValue(*p);
2818  if (hex_value == UINT_MAX)
2819  break;
2820 
2821  p++;
2822 
2823  // Store the number while we have space.
2824  if (bitPos) {
2825  bitPos -= 4;
2826  hex_value <<= bitPos % integerPartWidth;
2827  significand[bitPos / integerPartWidth] |= hex_value;
2828  } else if (!computedTrailingFraction) {
2829  auto FractOrErr = trailingHexadecimalFraction(p, end, hex_value);
2830  if (!FractOrErr)
2831  return FractOrErr.takeError();
2832  lost_fraction = *FractOrErr;
2833  computedTrailingFraction = true;
2834  }
2835  }
2836 
2837  /* Hex floats require an exponent but not a hexadecimal point. */
2838  if (p == end)
2839  return createError("Hex strings require an exponent");
2840  if (*p != 'p' && *p != 'P')
2841  return createError("Invalid character in significand");
2842  if (p == begin)
2843  return createError("Significand has no digits");
2844  if (dot != end && p - begin == 1)
2845  return createError("Significand has no digits");
2846 
2847  /* Ignore the exponent if we are zero. */
2848  if (p != firstSignificantDigit) {
2849  int expAdjustment;
2850 
2851  /* Implicit hexadecimal point? */
2852  if (dot == end)
2853  dot = p;
2854 
2855  /* Calculate the exponent adjustment implicit in the number of
2856  significant digits. */
2857  expAdjustment = static_cast<int>(dot - firstSignificantDigit);
2858  if (expAdjustment < 0)
2859  expAdjustment++;
2860  expAdjustment = expAdjustment * 4 - 1;
2861 
2862  /* Adjust for writing the significand starting at the most
2863  significant nibble. */
2864  expAdjustment += semantics->precision;
2865  expAdjustment -= partsCount * integerPartWidth;
2866 
2867  /* Adjust for the given exponent. */
2868  auto ExpOrErr = totalExponent(p + 1, end, expAdjustment);
2869  if (!ExpOrErr)
2870  return ExpOrErr.takeError();
2871  exponent = *ExpOrErr;
2872  }
2873 
2874  return normalize(rounding_mode, lost_fraction);
2875 }
