2877 IEEEFloat::opStatus
2878 IEEEFloat::roundSignificandWithExponent(const integerPart *decSigParts,
2879  unsigned sigPartCount, int exp,
2880  roundingMode rounding_mode) {
2881  unsigned int parts, pow5PartCount;
2882  fltSemantics calcSemantics = { 32767, -32767, 0, 0 };
2883  integerPart pow5Parts[maxPowerOfFiveParts];
2884  bool isNearest;
2885 
2886  isNearest = (rounding_mode == rmNearestTiesToEven ||
2887  rounding_mode == rmNearestTiesToAway);
2888 
2889  parts = partCountForBits(semantics->precision + 11);
2890 
2891  /* Calculate pow(5, abs(exp)). */
2892  pow5PartCount = powerOf5(pow5Parts, exp >= 0 ? exp: -exp);
2893 
2894  for (;; parts *= 2) {
2895  opStatus sigStatus, powStatus;
2896  unsigned int excessPrecision, truncatedBits;
2897 
2898  calcSemantics.precision = parts * integerPartWidth - 1;
2899  excessPrecision = calcSemantics.precision - semantics->precision;
2900  truncatedBits = excessPrecision;
2901 
2902  IEEEFloat decSig(calcSemantics, uninitialized);
2903  decSig.makeZero(sign);
2904  IEEEFloat pow5(calcSemantics);
2905 
2906  sigStatus = decSig.convertFromUnsignedParts(decSigParts, sigPartCount,
2907  rmNearestTiesToEven);
2908  powStatus = pow5.convertFromUnsignedParts(pow5Parts, pow5PartCount,
2909  rmNearestTiesToEven);
2910  /* Add exp, as 10^n = 5^n * 2^n. */
2911  decSig.exponent += exp;
2912 
2913  lostFraction calcLostFraction;
2914  integerPart HUerr, HUdistance;
2915  unsigned int powHUerr;
2916 
2917  if (exp >= 0) {
2918  /* multiplySignificand leaves the precision-th bit set to 1. */
2919  calcLostFraction = decSig.multiplySignificand(pow5);
2920  powHUerr = powStatus != opOK;
2921  } else {
2922  calcLostFraction = decSig.divideSignificand(pow5);
2923  /* Denormal numbers have less precision. */
2924  if (decSig.exponent < semantics->minExponent) {
2925  excessPrecision += (semantics->minExponent - decSig.exponent);
2926  truncatedBits = excessPrecision;
2927  if (excessPrecision > calcSemantics.precision)
2928  excessPrecision = calcSemantics.precision;
2929  }
2930  /* Extra half-ulp lost in reciprocal of exponent. */
2931  powHUerr = (powStatus == opOK && calcLostFraction == lfExactlyZero) ? 0:2;
2932  }
2933 
2934  /* Both multiplySignificand and divideSignificand return the
2935  result with the integer bit set. */
2936  assert(APInt::tcExtractBit
2937  (decSig.significandParts(), calcSemantics.precision - 1) == 1);
2938 
2939  HUerr = HUerrBound(calcLostFraction != lfExactlyZero, sigStatus != opOK,
2940  powHUerr);
2941  HUdistance = 2 * ulpsFromBoundary(decSig.significandParts(),
2942  excessPrecision, isNearest);
2943 
2944  /* Are we guaranteed to round correctly if we truncate? */
2945  if (HUdistance >= HUerr) {
2946  APInt::tcExtract(significandParts(), partCount(), decSig.significandParts(),
2947  calcSemantics.precision - excessPrecision,
2948  excessPrecision);
2949  /* Take the exponent of decSig. If we tcExtract-ed less bits
2950  above we must adjust our exponent to compensate for the
2951  implicit right shift. */
2952  exponent = (decSig.exponent + semantics->precision
2953  - (calcSemantics.precision - excessPrecision));
2954  calcLostFraction = lostFractionThroughTruncation(decSig.significandParts(),
2955  decSig.partCount(),
2956  truncatedBits);
2957  return normalize(rounding_mode, calcLostFraction);
2958  }
2959  }
2960 }

2962 Expected<IEEEFloat::opStatus>
2963 IEEEFloat::convertFromDecimalString(StringRef str, roundingMode rounding_mode) {
2964  decimalInfo D;
2965  opStatus fs;
2966 
2967  /* Scan the text. */
2968  StringRef::iterator p = str.begin();
2969  if (Error Err = interpretDecimal(p, str.end(), &D))
2970  return std::move(Err);
2971 
2972  /* Handle the quick cases. First the case of no significant digits,
2973  i.e. zero, and then exponents that are obviously too large or too
2974  small. Writing L for log 10 / log 2, a number d.ddddd*10^exp
2975  definitely overflows if
2976 
2977  (exp - 1) * L >= maxExponent
2978 
2979  and definitely underflows to zero where
2980 
2981  (exp + 1) * L <= minExponent - precision
2982 
2983  With integer arithmetic the tightest bounds for L are
2984 
2985  93/28 < L < 196/59 [ numerator <= 256 ]
2986  42039/12655 < L < 28738/8651 [ numerator <= 65536 ]
2987  */
2988 
2989  // Test if we have a zero number allowing for strings with no null terminators
2990  // and zero decimals with non-zero exponents.
2991  //
2992  // We computed firstSigDigit by ignoring all zeros and dots. Thus if
2993  // D->firstSigDigit equals str.end(), every digit must be a zero and there can
2994  // be at most one dot. On the other hand, if we have a zero with a non-zero
2995  // exponent, then we know that D.firstSigDigit will be non-numeric.
2996  if (D.firstSigDigit == str.end() || decDigitValue(*D.firstSigDigit) >= 10U) {
2997  category = fcZero;
2998  fs = opOK;
2999  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
3000  sign = false;
3001 
3002  /* Check whether the normalized exponent is high enough to overflow
3003  max during the log-rebasing in the max-exponent check below. */
3004  } else if (D.normalizedExponent - 1 > INT_MAX / 42039) {
3005  fs = handleOverflow(rounding_mode);
3006 
3007  /* If it wasn't, then it also wasn't high enough to overflow max
3008  during the log-rebasing in the min-exponent check. Check that it
3009  won't overflow min in either check, then perform the min-exponent
3010  check. */
3011  } else if (D.normalizedExponent - 1 < INT_MIN / 42039 ||
3012  (D.normalizedExponent + 1) * 28738 <=
3013  8651 * (semantics->minExponent - (int) semantics->precision)) {
3014  /* Underflow to zero and round. */
3015  category = fcNormal;
3016  zeroSignificand();
3017  fs = normalize(rounding_mode, lfLessThanHalf);
3018 
3019  /* We can finally safely perform the max-exponent check. */
3020  } else if ((D.normalizedExponent - 1) * 42039
3021  >= 12655 * semantics->maxExponent) {
3022  /* Overflow and round. */
3023  fs = handleOverflow(rounding_mode);
3024  } else {
3025  integerPart *decSignificand;
3026  unsigned int partCount;
3027 
3028  /* A tight upper bound on number of bits required to hold an
3029  N-digit decimal integer is N * 196 / 59. Allocate enough space
3030  to hold the full significand, and an extra part required by
3031  tcMultiplyPart. */
3032  partCount = static_cast<unsigned int>(D.lastSigDigit - D.firstSigDigit) + 1;
3033  partCount = partCountForBits(1 + 196 * partCount / 59);
3034  decSignificand = new integerPart[partCount + 1];
3035  partCount = 0;
3036 
3037  /* Convert to binary efficiently - we do almost all multiplication
3038  in an integerPart. When this would overflow do we do a single
3039  bignum multiplication, and then revert again to multiplication
3040  in an integerPart. */
3041  do {
3042  integerPart decValue, val, multiplier;
3043 
3044  val = 0;
3045  multiplier = 1;
3046 
3047  do {
3048  if (*p == '.') {
3049  p++;
3050  if (p == str.end()) {
3051  break;
3052  }
3053  }
3054  decValue = decDigitValue(*p++);
3055  if (decValue >= 10U) {
3056  delete[] decSignificand;
3057  return createError("Invalid character in significand");
3058  }
3059  multiplier *= 10;
3060  val = val * 10 + decValue;
3061  /* The maximum number that can be multiplied by ten with any
3062  digit added without overflowing an integerPart. */
3063  } while (p <= D.lastSigDigit && multiplier <= (~ (integerPart) 0 - 9) / 10);
3064 
3065  /* Multiply out the current part. */
3066  APInt::tcMultiplyPart(decSignificand, decSignificand, multiplier, val,
3067  partCount, partCount + 1, false);
3068 
3069  /* If we used another part (likely but not guaranteed), increase
3070  the count. */
3071  if (decSignificand[partCount])
3072  partCount++;
3073  } while (p <= D.lastSigDigit);
3074 
3075  category = fcNormal;
3076  fs = roundSignificandWithExponent(decSignificand, partCount,
3077  D.exponent, rounding_mode);
3078 
3079  delete [] decSignificand;
3080  }
3081 
3082  return fs;
3083 }

3190  If UPPERCASE, the output is in upper case, otherwise in lower case.
3191 
3192  HEXDIGITS digits appear altogether, rounding the value if
3193  necessary. If HEXDIGITS is 0, the minimal precision to display the
3194  number precisely is used instead. If nothing would appear after
3195  the decimal point it is suppressed.
3196 
3197  The decimal exponent is always printed and has at least one digit.
3198  Zero values display an exponent of zero. Infinities and NaNs
3199  appear as "infinity" or "nan" respectively.
3200 
3201  The above rules are as specified by C99. There is ambiguity about
3202  what the leading hexadecimal digit should be. This implementation
3203  uses whatever is necessary so that the exponent is displayed as
3204  stored. This implies the exponent will fall within the IEEE format
3205  range, and the leading hexadecimal digit will be 0 (for denormals),
3206  1 (normal numbers) or 2 (normal numbers rounded-away-from-zero with
3207  any other digits zero).
3208 */
3209 unsigned int IEEEFloat::convertToHexString(char *dst, unsigned int hexDigits,
3210  bool upperCase,
3211  roundingMode rounding_mode) const {
3212  char *p;
3213 
3214  p = dst;
3215  if (sign)
3216  *dst++ = '-';
3217 
3218  switch (category) {
3219  case fcInfinity:
3220  memcpy (dst, upperCase ? infinityU: infinityL, sizeof infinityU - 1);
3221  dst += sizeof infinityL - 1;
3222  break;
3223 
3224  case fcNaN:
3225  memcpy (dst, upperCase ? NaNU: NaNL, sizeof NaNU - 1);
3226  dst += sizeof NaNU - 1;
3227  break;
3228 
3229  case fcZero:
3230  *dst++ = '0';
3231  *dst++ = upperCase ? 'X': 'x';
3232  *dst++ = '0';
3233  if (hexDigits > 1) {
3234  *dst++ = '.';
3235  memset (dst, '0', hexDigits - 1);
3236  dst += hexDigits - 1;
3237  }
3238  *dst++ = upperCase ? 'P': 'p';
3239  *dst++ = '0';
3240  break;
3241 
3242  case fcNormal:
3243  dst = convertNormalToHexString (dst, hexDigits, upperCase, rounding_mode);
3244  break;
3245  }
3246 
3247  *dst = 0;
3248 
3249  return static_cast<unsigned int>(dst - p);
3250 }

3252 /* Does the hard work of outputting the correctly rounded hexadecimal
3253  form of a normal floating point number with the specified number of
3254  hexadecimal digits. If HEXDIGITS is zero the minimum number of
3255  digits necessary to print the value precisely is output. */
3256 char *IEEEFloat::convertNormalToHexString(char *dst, unsigned int hexDigits,
3257  bool upperCase,
3258  roundingMode rounding_mode) const {
3259  unsigned int count, valueBits, shift, partsCount, outputDigits;
3260  const char *hexDigitChars;
3261  const integerPart *significand;
3262  char *p;
3263  bool roundUp;
3264 
3265  *dst++ = '0';
3266  *dst++ = upperCase ? 'X': 'x';
3267 
3268  roundUp = false;
3269  hexDigitChars = upperCase ? hexDigitsUpper: hexDigitsLower;
3270 
3271  significand = significandParts();
3272  partsCount = partCount();
3273 
3274  /* +3 because the first digit only uses the single integer bit, so
3275  we have 3 virtual zero most-significant-bits. */
3276  valueBits = semantics->precision + 3;
3277  shift = integerPartWidth - valueBits % integerPartWidth;
3278 
3279  /* The natural number of digits required ignoring trailing
3280  insignificant zeroes. */
3281  outputDigits = (valueBits - significandLSB () + 3) / 4;
3282 
3283  /* hexDigits of zero means use the required number for the
3284  precision. Otherwise, see if we are truncating. If we are,
3285  find out if we need to round away from zero. */
3286  if (hexDigits) {
3287  if (hexDigits < outputDigits) {
3288  /* We are dropping non-zero bits, so need to check how to round.
3289  "bits" is the number of dropped bits. */
3290  unsigned int bits;
3291  lostFraction fraction;
3292 
3293  bits = valueBits - hexDigits * 4;
3294  fraction = lostFractionThroughTruncation (significand, partsCount, bits);
3295  roundUp = roundAwayFromZero(rounding_mode, fraction, bits);
3296  }
3297  outputDigits = hexDigits;
3298  }
3299 
3300  /* Write the digits consecutively, and start writing in the location
3301  of the hexadecimal point. We move the most significant digit
3302  left and add the hexadecimal point later. */
3303  p = ++dst;
3304 
3305  count = (valueBits + integerPartWidth - 1) / integerPartWidth;
3306 
3307  while (outputDigits && count) {
3308  integerPart part;
3309 
3310  /* Put the most significant integerPartWidth bits in "part". */
3311  if (--count == partsCount)
3312  part = 0; /* An imaginary higher zero part. */
3313  else
3314  part = significand[count] << shift;
3315 
3316  if (count && shift)
3317  part |= significand[count - 1] >> (integerPartWidth - shift);
3318 
3319  /* Convert as much of "part" to hexdigits as we can. */
3320  unsigned int curDigits = integerPartWidth / 4;
3321 
3322  if (curDigits > outputDigits)
3323  curDigits = outputDigits;
3324  dst += partAsHex (dst, part, curDigits, hexDigitChars);
3325  outputDigits -= curDigits;
3326  }
3327 
3328  if (roundUp) {
3329  char *q = dst;
3330 
3331  /* Note that hexDigitChars has a trailing '0'. */
3332  do {
3333  q--;
3334  *q = hexDigitChars[hexDigitValue (*q) + 1];
3335  } while (*q == '0');
3336  assert(q >= p);
3337  } else {
3338  /* Add trailing zeroes. */
3339  memset (dst, '0', outputDigits);
3340  dst += outputDigits;
3341  }
3342 
3343  /* Move the most significant digit to before the point, and if there
3344  is something after the decimal point add it. This must come
3345  after rounding above. */
3346  p[-1] = p[0];
3347  if (dst -1 == p)
3348  dst--;
3349  else
3350  p[0] = '.';
3351 
3352  /* Finally output the exponent. */
3353  *dst++ = upperCase ? 'P': 'p';
3354 
3355  return writeSignedDecimal (dst, exponent);
3356 }

3358 hash_code hash_value(const IEEEFloat &Arg) {
3359  if (!Arg.isFiniteNonZero())
3360  return hash_combine((uint8_t)Arg.category,
3361  // NaN has no sign, fix it at zero.
3362  Arg.isNaN() ? (uint8_t)0 : (uint8_t)Arg.sign,
3363  Arg.semantics->precision);
3364 
3365  // Normal floats need their exponent and significand hashed.
3366  return hash_combine((uint8_t)Arg.category, (uint8_t)Arg.sign,
3367  Arg.semantics->precision, Arg.exponent,
3368  hash_combine_range(
3369  Arg.significandParts(),
3370  Arg.significandParts() + Arg.partCount()));

3373 // Conversion from APFloat to/from host float/double. It may eventually be
3374 // possible to eliminate these and have everybody deal with APFloats, but that
3375 // will take a while. This approach will not easily extend to long double.
3376 // Current implementation requires integerPartWidth==64, which is correct at
3377 // the moment but could be made more general.
3378 
3379 // Denormals have exponent minExponent in APFloat, but minExponent-1 in
3380 // the actual IEEE respresentations. We compensate for that here.
3381 
3382 APInt IEEEFloat::convertF80LongDoubleAPFloatToAPInt() const {
3383  assert(semantics == (const llvm::fltSemantics*)&semX87DoubleExtended);
3384  assert(partCount()==2);
3385 
3386  uint64_t myexponent, mysignificand;
3387 
3388  if (isFiniteNonZero()) {
3389  myexponent = exponent+16383; //bias
3390  mysignificand = significandParts()[0];
3391  if (myexponent==1 && !(mysignificand & 0x8000000000000000ULL))
3392  myexponent = 0; // denormal
3393  } else if (category==fcZero) {
3394  myexponent = 0;
3395  mysignificand = 0;
3396  } else if (category==fcInfinity) {
3397  myexponent = 0x7fff;
3398  mysignificand = 0x8000000000000000ULL;
3399  } else {
3400  assert(category == fcNaN && "Unknown category");
3401  myexponent = 0x7fff;
3402  mysignificand = significandParts()[0];
3403  }
3404 
3405  uint64_t words[2];
3406  words[0] = mysignificand;
3407  words[1] = ((uint64_t)(sign & 1) << 15) |
3408  (myexponent & 0x7fffLL);
3409  return APInt(80, words);
3410 }

3412 APInt IEEEFloat::convertPPCDoubleDoubleAPFloatToAPInt() const {
3413  assert(semantics == (const llvm::fltSemantics *)&semPPCDoubleDoubleLegacy);
3414  assert(partCount()==2);
3415 
3416  uint64_t words[2];
3417  opStatus fs;
3418  bool losesInfo;
3419 
3420  // Convert number to double. To avoid spurious underflows, we re-
3421  // normalize against the "double" minExponent first, and only *then*
3422  // truncate the mantissa. The result of that second conversion
3423  // may be inexact, but should never underflow.
3424  // Declare fltSemantics before APFloat that uses it (and
3425  // saves pointer to it) to ensure correct destruction order.
3426  fltSemantics extendedSemantics = *semantics;
3427  extendedSemantics.minExponent = semIEEEdouble.minExponent;
3428  IEEEFloat extended(*this);
3429  fs = extended.convert(extendedSemantics, rmNearestTiesToEven, &losesInfo);
3430  assert(fs == opOK && !losesInfo);
3431  (void)fs;
3432 
3433  IEEEFloat u(extended);
3434  fs = u.convert(semIEEEdouble, rmNearestTiesToEven, &losesInfo);
3435  assert(fs == opOK || fs == opInexact);
3436  (void)fs;
3437  words[0] = *u.convertDoubleAPFloatToAPInt().getRawData();
3438 
3439  // If conversion was exact or resulted in a special case, we're done;
3440  // just set the second double to zero. Otherwise, re-convert back to
3441  // the extended format and compute the difference. This now should
3442  // convert exactly to double.
3443  if (u.isFiniteNonZero() && losesInfo) {
3444  fs = u.convert(extendedSemantics, rmNearestTiesToEven, &losesInfo);
3445  assert(fs == opOK && !losesInfo);
3446  (void)fs;
3447 
3448  IEEEFloat v(extended);
3449  v.subtract(u, rmNearestTiesToEven);
3450  fs = v.convert(semIEEEdouble, rmNearestTiesToEven, &losesInfo);
3451  assert(fs == opOK && !losesInfo);
3452  (void)fs;
3453  words[1] = *v.convertDoubleAPFloatToAPInt().getRawData();
3454  } else {
3455  words[1] = 0;
3456  }
3457 
3458  return APInt(128, words);
3459 }

3766 /// Integer bit is explicit in this format. Intel hardware (387 and later)
3767 /// does not support these bit patterns:
3768 /// exponent = all 1's, integer bit 0, significand 0 ("pseudoinfinity")
3769 /// exponent = all 1's, integer bit 0, significand nonzero ("pseudoNaN")
3770 /// exponent!=0 nor all 1's, integer bit 0 ("unnormal")
3771 /// exponent = 0, integer bit 1 ("pseudodenormal")
3772 /// At the moment, the first three are treated as NaNs, the last one as Normal.
3773 void IEEEFloat::initFromF80LongDoubleAPInt(const APInt &api) {
3774  uint64_t i1 = api.getRawData()[0];
3775  uint64_t i2 = api.getRawData()[1];
3776  uint64_t myexponent = (i2 & 0x7fff);
3777  uint64_t mysignificand = i1;
3778  uint8_t myintegerbit = mysignificand >> 63;
3779 
3780  initialize(&semX87DoubleExtended);
3781  assert(partCount()==2);
3782 
3783  sign = static_cast<unsigned int>(i2>>15);
3784  if (myexponent == 0 && mysignificand == 0) {
3785  makeZero(sign);
3786  } else if (myexponent==0x7fff && mysignificand==0x8000000000000000ULL) {
3787  makeInf(sign);
3788  } else if ((myexponent == 0x7fff && mysignificand != 0x8000000000000000ULL) ||
3789  (myexponent != 0x7fff && myexponent != 0 && myintegerbit == 0)) {
3790  category = fcNaN;
3791  exponent = exponentNaN();
3792  significandParts()[0] = mysignificand;
3793  significandParts()[1] = 0;
3794  } else {
3795  category = fcNormal;
3796  exponent = myexponent - 16383;
3797  significandParts()[0] = mysignificand;
3798  significandParts()[1] = 0;
3799  if (myexponent==0) // denormal
3800  exponent = -16382;
3801  }
3802 }

4109 /// Make this number the largest magnitude normal number in the given
4110 /// semantics.
4111 void IEEEFloat::makeLargest(bool Negative) {
4112  // We want (in interchange format):
4113  // sign = {Negative}
4114  // exponent = 1..10
4115  // significand = 1..1
4116  category = fcNormal;
4117  sign = Negative;
4118  exponent = semantics->maxExponent;
4119 
4120  // Use memset to set all but the highest integerPart to all ones.
4121  integerPart *significand = significandParts();
4122  unsigned PartCount = partCount();
4123  memset(significand, 0xFF, sizeof(integerPart)*(PartCount - 1));
4124 
4125  // Set the high integerPart especially setting all unused top bits for
4126  // internal consistency.
4127  const unsigned NumUnusedHighBits =
4128  PartCount*integerPartWidth - semantics->precision;
4129  significand[PartCount - 1] = (NumUnusedHighBits < integerPartWidth)
4130  ? (~integerPart(0) >> NumUnusedHighBits)
4131  : 0;
4132 
4133  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly &&
4134  semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::AllOnes)
4135  significand[0] &= ~integerPart(1);
4136 }

4181  /// Removes data from the given significand until it is no more
4182  /// precise than is required for the desired precision.
4183  void AdjustToPrecision(APInt &significand,
4184  int &exp, unsigned FormatPrecision) {
4185  unsigned bits = significand.getActiveBits();
4186 
4187  // 196/59 is a very slight overestimate of lg_2(10).
4188  unsigned bitsRequired = (FormatPrecision * 196 + 58) / 59;
4189 
4190  if (bits <= bitsRequired) return;
4191 
4192  unsigned tensRemovable = (bits - bitsRequired) * 59 / 196;
4193  if (!tensRemovable) return;
4194 
4195  exp += tensRemovable;
4196 
4197  APInt divisor(significand.getBitWidth(), 1);
4198  APInt powten(significand.getBitWidth(), 10);
4199  while (true) {
4200  if (tensRemovable & 1)
4201  divisor *= powten;
4202  tensRemovable >>= 1;
4203  if (!tensRemovable) break;
4204  powten *= powten;
4205  }
4206 
4207  significand = significand.udiv(divisor);
4208 
4209  // Truncate the significand down to its active bit count.
4210  significand = significand.trunc(significand.getActiveBits());
4211  }
4212 
4213 
4214  void AdjustToPrecision(SmallVectorImpl<char> &buffer,
4215  int &exp, unsigned FormatPrecision) {
4216  unsigned N = buffer.size();
4217  if (N <= FormatPrecision) return;
4218 
4219  // The most significant figures are the last ones in the buffer.
4220  unsigned FirstSignificant = N - FormatPrecision;
4221 
4222  // Round.
4223  // FIXME: this probably shouldn't use 'round half up'.
4224 
4225  // Rounding down is just a truncation, except we also want to drop
4226  // trailing zeros from the new result.
4227  if (buffer[FirstSignificant - 1] < '5') {
4228  while (FirstSignificant < N && buffer[FirstSignificant] == '0')
4229  FirstSignificant++;
4230 
4231  exp += FirstSignificant;
4232  buffer.erase(&buffer[0], &buffer[FirstSignificant]);
4233  return;
4234  }
4235 
4236  // Rounding up requires a decimal add-with-carry. If we continue
4237  // the carry, the newly-introduced zeros will just be truncated.
4238  for (unsigned I = FirstSignificant; I != N; ++I) {
4239  if (buffer[I] == '9') {
4240  FirstSignificant++;
4241  } else {
4242  buffer[I]++;
4243  break;
4244  }
4245  }
4246 
4247  // If we carried through, we have exactly one digit of precision.
4248  if (FirstSignificant == N) {
4249  exp += FirstSignificant;
4250  buffer.clear();
4251  buffer.push_back('1');
4252  return;
4253  }
4254 
4255  exp += FirstSignificant;
4256  buffer.erase(&buffer[0], &buffer[FirstSignificant]);
4257  }
4258 } // namespace

4260 void IEEEFloat::toString(SmallVectorImpl<char> &Str, unsigned FormatPrecision,
4261  unsigned FormatMaxPadding, bool TruncateZero) const {
4262  switch (category) {
4263  case fcInfinity:
4264  if (isNegative())
4265  return append(Str, "-Inf");
4266  else
4267  return append(Str, "+Inf");
4268 
4269  case fcNaN: return append(Str, "NaN");
4270 
4271  case fcZero:
4272  if (isNegative())
4273  Str.push_back('-');
4274 
4275  if (!FormatMaxPadding) {
4276  if (TruncateZero)
4277  append(Str, "0.0E+0");
4278  else {
4279  append(Str, "0.0");
4280  if (FormatPrecision > 1)
4281  Str.append(FormatPrecision - 1, '0');
4282  append(Str, "e+00");
4283  }
4284  } else
4285  Str.push_back('0');
4286  return;
4287 
4288  case fcNormal:
4289  break;
4290  }
4291 
4292  if (isNegative())
4293  Str.push_back('-');
4294 
4295  // Decompose the number into an APInt and an exponent.
4296  int exp = exponent - ((int) semantics->precision - 1);
4297  APInt significand(
4298  semantics->precision,
4299  ArrayRef(significandParts(), partCountForBits(semantics->precision)));
4300 
4301  // Set FormatPrecision if zero. We want to do this before we
4302  // truncate trailing zeros, as those are part of the precision.
4303  if (!FormatPrecision) {
4304  // We use enough digits so the number can be round-tripped back to an
4305  // APFloat. The formula comes from "How to Print Floating-Point Numbers
4306  // Accurately" by Steele and White.
4307  // FIXME: Using a formula based purely on the precision is conservative;
4308  // we can print fewer digits depending on the actual value being printed.
4309 
4310  // FormatPrecision = 2 + floor(significandBits / lg_2(10))
4311  FormatPrecision = 2 + semantics->precision * 59 / 196;
4312  }
4313 
4314  // Ignore trailing binary zeros.
4315  int trailingZeros = significand.countTrailingZeros();
4316  exp += trailingZeros;
4317  significand.lshrInPlace(trailingZeros);
4318 
4319  // Change the exponent from 2^e to 10^e.
4320  if (exp == 0) {
4321  // Nothing to do.
4322  } else if (exp > 0) {
4323  // Just shift left.
4324  significand = significand.zext(semantics->precision + exp);
4325  significand <<= exp;
4326  exp = 0;
4327  } else { /* exp < 0 */
4328  int texp = -exp;
4329 
4330  // We transform this using the identity:
4331  // (N)(2^-e) == (N)(5^e)(10^-e)
4332  // This means we have to multiply N (the significand) by 5^e.
4333  // To avoid overflow, we have to operate on numbers large
4334  // enough to store N * 5^e:
4335  // log2(N * 5^e) == log2(N) + e * log2(5)
4336  // <= semantics->precision + e * 137 / 59
4337  // (log_2(5) ~ 2.321928 < 2.322034 ~ 137/59)
4338 
4339  unsigned precision = semantics->precision + (137 * texp + 136) / 59;
4340 
4341  // Multiply significand by 5^e.
4342  // N * 5^0101 == N * 5^(1*1) * 5^(0*2) * 5^(1*4) * 5^(0*8)
4343  significand = significand.zext(precision);
4344  APInt five_to_the_i(precision, 5);
4345  while (true) {
4346  if (texp & 1) significand *= five_to_the_i;
4347 
4348  texp >>= 1;
4349  if (!texp) break;
4350  five_to_the_i *= five_to_the_i;
4351  }
4352  }
4353 
4354  AdjustToPrecision(significand, exp, FormatPrecision);
4355 
4356  SmallVector<char, 256> buffer;
4357 
4358  // Fill the buffer.
4359  unsigned precision = significand.getBitWidth();
4360  if (precision < 4) {
4361  // We need enough precision to store the value 10.
4362  precision = 4;
4363  significand = significand.zext(precision);
4364  }
4365  APInt ten(precision, 10);
4366  APInt digit(precision, 0);
4367 
4368  bool inTrail = true;
4369  while (significand != 0) {
4370  // digit <- significand % 10
4371  // significand <- significand / 10
4372  APInt::udivrem(significand, ten, significand, digit);
4373 
4374  unsigned d = digit.getZExtValue();
4375 
4376  // Drop trailing zeros.
4377  if (inTrail && !d) exp++;
4378  else {
4379  buffer.push_back((char) ('0' + d));
4380  inTrail = false;
4381  }
4382  }
4383 
4384  assert(!buffer.empty() && "no characters in buffer!");
4385 
4386  // Drop down to FormatPrecision.
4387  // TODO: don't do more precise calculations above than are required.
4388  AdjustToPrecision(buffer, exp, FormatPrecision);
4389 
4390  unsigned NDigits = buffer.size();
4391 
4392  // Check whether we should use scientific notation.
4393  bool FormatScientific;
4394  if (!FormatMaxPadding)
4395  FormatScientific = true;
4396  else {
4397  if (exp >= 0) {
4398  // 765e3 --> 765000
4399  // ^^^
4400  // But we shouldn't make the number look more precise than it is.
4401  FormatScientific = ((unsigned) exp > FormatMaxPadding ||
4402  NDigits + (unsigned) exp > FormatPrecision);
4403  } else {
4404  // Power of the most significant digit.
4405  int MSD = exp + (int) (NDigits - 1);
4406  if (MSD >= 0) {
4407  // 765e-2 == 7.65
4408  FormatScientific = false;
4409  } else {
4410  // 765e-5 == 0.00765
4411  // ^ ^^
4412  FormatScientific = ((unsigned) -MSD) > FormatMaxPadding;
4413  }
4414  }
4415  }
4416 
4417  // Scientific formatting is pretty straightforward.
4418  if (FormatScientific) {
4419  exp += (NDigits - 1);
4420 
4421  Str.push_back(buffer[NDigits-1]);
4422  Str.push_back('.');
4423  if (NDigits == 1 && TruncateZero)
4424  Str.push_back('0');
4425  else
4426  for (unsigned I = 1; I != NDigits; ++I)
4427  Str.push_back(buffer[NDigits-1-I]);
4428  // Fill with zeros up to FormatPrecision.
4429  if (!TruncateZero && FormatPrecision > NDigits - 1)
4430  Str.append(FormatPrecision - NDigits + 1, '0');
4431  // For !TruncateZero we use lower 'e'.
4432  Str.push_back(TruncateZero ? 'E' : 'e');
4433 
4434  Str.push_back(exp >= 0 ? '+' : '-');
4435  if (exp < 0) exp = -exp;
4436  SmallVector<char, 6> expbuf;
4437  do {
4438  expbuf.push_back((char) ('0' + (exp % 10)));
4439  exp /= 10;
4440  } while (exp);
4441  // Exponent always at least two digits if we do not truncate zeros.
4442  if (!TruncateZero && expbuf.size() < 2)
4443  expbuf.push_back('0');
4444  for (unsigned I = 0, E = expbuf.size(); I != E; ++I)
4445  Str.push_back(expbuf[E-1-I]);
4446  return;
4447  }
4448 
4449  // Non-scientific, positive exponents.
4450  if (exp >= 0) {
4451  for (unsigned I = 0; I != NDigits; ++I)
4452  Str.push_back(buffer[NDigits-1-I]);
4453  for (unsigned I = 0; I != (unsigned) exp; ++I)
4454  Str.push_back('0');
4455  return;
4456  }
4457 
4458  // Non-scientific, negative exponents.
4459 
4460  // The number of digits to the left of the decimal point.
4461  int NWholeDigits = exp + (int) NDigits;
4462 
4463  unsigned I = 0;
4464  if (NWholeDigits > 0) {
4465  for (; I != (unsigned) NWholeDigits; ++I)
4466  Str.push_back(buffer[NDigits-I-1]);
4467  Str.push_back('.');
4468  } else {
4469  unsigned NZeros = 1 + (unsigned) -NWholeDigits;
4470 
4471  Str.push_back('0');
4472  Str.push_back('.');
4473  for (unsigned Z = 1; Z != NZeros; ++Z)
4474  Str.push_back('0');
4475  }
4476 
4477  for (; I != NDigits; ++I)
4478  Str.push_back(buffer[NDigits-I-1]);
4479 }

4481 bool IEEEFloat::getExactInverse(APFloat *inv) const {
4482  // Special floats and denormals have no exact inverse.
4483  if (!isFiniteNonZero())
4484  return false;
4485 
4486  // Check that the number is a power of two by making sure that only the
4487  // integer bit is set in the significand.
4488  if (significandLSB() != semantics->precision - 1)
4489  return false;
4490 
4491  // Get the inverse.
4492  IEEEFloat reciprocal(*semantics, 1ULL);
4493  if (reciprocal.divide(*this, rmNearestTiesToEven) != opOK)
4494  return false;
4495 
4496  // Avoid multiplication with a denormal, it is not safe on all platforms and
4497  // may be slower than a normal division.
4498  if (reciprocal.isDenormal())
4499  return false;
4500 
4501  assert(reciprocal.isFiniteNonZero() &&
4502  reciprocal.significandLSB() == reciprocal.semantics->precision - 1);
4503 
4504  if (inv)
4505  *inv = APFloat(reciprocal, *semantics);
4506 
4507  return true;
4508 }

4510 bool IEEEFloat::isSignaling() const {
4511  if (!isNaN())
4512  return false;
4513  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly)
4514  return false;
4515 
4516  // IEEE-754R 2008 6.2.1: A signaling NaN bit string should be encoded with the
4517  // first bit of the trailing significand being 0.
4518  return !APInt::tcExtractBit(significandParts(), semantics->precision - 2);
4519 }
4520 
4521 /// IEEE-754R 2008 5.3.1: nextUp/nextDown.
4522 ///
4523 /// *NOTE* since nextDown(x) = -nextUp(-x), we only implement nextUp with
4524 /// appropriate sign switching before/after the computation.
4525 IEEEFloat::opStatus IEEEFloat::next(bool nextDown) {
4526  // If we are performing nextDown, swap sign so we have -x.
4527  if (nextDown)
4528  changeSign();
4529 
4530  // Compute nextUp(x)
4531  opStatus result = opOK;
4532 
4533  // Handle each float category separately.
4534  switch (category) {
4535  case fcInfinity:
4536  // nextUp(+inf) = +inf
4537  if (!isNegative())
4538  break;
4539  // nextUp(-inf) = -getLargest()
4540  makeLargest(true);
4541  break;
4542  case fcNaN:
4543  // IEEE-754R 2008 6.2 Par 2: nextUp(sNaN) = qNaN. Set Invalid flag.
4544  // IEEE-754R 2008 6.2: nextUp(qNaN) = qNaN. Must be identity so we do not
4545  // change the payload.
4546  if (isSignaling()) {
4547  result = opInvalidOp;
4548  // For consistency, propagate the sign of the sNaN to the qNaN.
4549  makeNaN(false, isNegative(), nullptr);
4550  }
4551  break;
4552  case fcZero:
4553  // nextUp(pm 0) = +getSmallest()
4554  makeSmallest(false);
4555  break;
4556  case fcNormal:
4557  // nextUp(-getSmallest()) = -0
4558  if (isSmallest() && isNegative()) {
4559  APInt::tcSet(significandParts(), 0, partCount());
4560  category = fcZero;
4561  exponent = 0;
4562  if (semantics->nanEncoding == fltNanEncoding::NegativeZero)
4563  sign = false;
4564  break;
4565  }
4566 
4567  if (isLargest() && !isNegative()) {
4568  if (semantics->nonFiniteBehavior == fltNonfiniteBehavior::NanOnly) {
4569  // nextUp(getLargest()) == NAN
4570  makeNaN();
4571  break;
4572  } else {
4573  // nextUp(getLargest()) == INFINITY
4574  APInt::tcSet(significandParts(), 0, partCount());
4575  category = fcInfinity;
4576  exponent = semantics->maxExponent + 1;
4577  break;
4578  }
4579  }
4580 
4581  // nextUp(normal) == normal + inc.
4582  if (isNegative()) {
4583  // If we are negative, we need to decrement the significand.
4584 
4585  // We only cross a binade boundary that requires adjusting the exponent
4586  // if:
4587  // 1. exponent != semantics->minExponent. This implies we are not in the
4588  // smallest binade or are dealing with denormals.
4589  // 2. Our significand excluding the integral bit is all zeros.
4590  bool WillCrossBinadeBoundary =
4591  exponent != semantics->minExponent && isSignificandAllZeros();
4592 
4593  // Decrement the significand.
4594  //
4595  // We always do this since:
4596  // 1. If we are dealing with a non-binade decrement, by definition we
4597  // just decrement the significand.
4598  // 2. If we are dealing with a normal -> normal binade decrement, since
4599  // we have an explicit integral bit the fact that all bits but the
4600  // integral bit are zero implies that subtracting one will yield a
4601  // significand with 0 integral bit and 1 in all other spots. Thus we
4602  // must just adjust the exponent and set the integral bit to 1.
4603  // 3. If we are dealing with a normal -> denormal binade decrement,
4604  // since we set the integral bit to 0 when we represent denormals, we
4605  // just decrement the significand.
4606  integerPart *Parts = significandParts();
4607  APInt::tcDecrement(Parts, partCount());
4608 
4609  if (WillCrossBinadeBoundary) {
4610  // Our result is a normal number. Do the following:
4611  // 1. Set the integral bit to 1.
4612  // 2. Decrement the exponent.
4613  APInt::tcSetBit(Parts, semantics->precision - 1);
4614  exponent--;
4615  }
4616  } else {
4617  // If we are positive, we need to increment the significand.
4618 
4619  // We only cross a binade boundary that requires adjusting the exponent if
4620  // the input is not a denormal and all of said input's significand bits
4621  // are set. If all of said conditions are true: clear the significand, set
4622  // the integral bit to 1, and increment the exponent. If we have a
4623  // denormal always increment since moving denormals and the numbers in the
4624  // smallest normal binade have the same exponent in our representation.
4625  bool WillCrossBinadeBoundary = !isDenormal() && isSignificandAllOnes();
4626 
4627  if (WillCrossBinadeBoundary) {
4628  integerPart *Parts = significandParts();
4629  APInt::tcSet(Parts, 0, partCount());
4630  APInt::tcSetBit(Parts, semantics->precision - 1);
4631  assert(exponent != semantics->maxExponent &&
4632  "We can not increment an exponent beyond the maxExponent allowed"
4633  " by the given floating point semantics.");
4634  exponent++;
4635  } else {
4636  incrementSignificand();
4637  }
4638  }
4639  break;
4640  }
4641 
4642  // If we are performing nextDown, swap sign so we have -nextUp(-x)
4643  if (nextDown)
4644  changeSign();
4645 
4646  return result;
4647 }

4695 int ilogb(const IEEEFloat &Arg) {
4696  if (Arg.isNaN())
4697  return IEEEFloat::IEK_NaN;
4698  if (Arg.isZero())
4699  return IEEEFloat::IEK_Zero;
4700  if (Arg.isInfinity())
4701  return IEEEFloat::IEK_Inf;
4702  if (!Arg.isDenormal())
4703  return Arg.exponent;
4704 
4705  IEEEFloat Normalized(Arg);
4706  int SignificandBits = Arg.getSemantics().precision - 1;
4707 
4708  Normalized.exponent += SignificandBits;
4709  Normalized.normalize(IEEEFloat::rmNearestTiesToEven, lfExactlyZero);
4710  return Normalized.exponent - SignificandBits;
4711 }

4713 IEEEFloat scalbn(IEEEFloat X, int Exp, IEEEFloat::roundingMode RoundingMode) {
4714  auto MaxExp = X.getSemantics().maxExponent;
4715  auto MinExp = X.getSemantics().minExponent;
4716 
4717  // If Exp is wildly out-of-scale, simply adding it to X.exponent will
4718  // overflow; clamp it to a safe range before adding, but ensure that the range
4719  // is large enough that the clamp does not change the result. The range we
4720  // need to support is the difference between the largest possible exponent and
4721  // the normalized exponent of half the smallest denormal.
4722 
4723  int SignificandBits = X.getSemantics().precision - 1;
4724  int MaxIncrement = MaxExp - (MinExp - SignificandBits) + 1;
4725 
4726  // Clamp to one past the range ends to let normalize handle overlflow.
4727  X.exponent += std::clamp(Exp, -MaxIncrement - 1, MaxIncrement);
4728  X.normalize(RoundingMode, lfExactlyZero);
4729  if (X.isNaN())
4730  X.makeQuiet();
4731  return X;
4732 }

4734 IEEEFloat frexp(const IEEEFloat &Val, int &Exp, IEEEFloat::roundingMode RM) {
4735  Exp = ilogb(Val);
4736 
4737  // Quiet signalling nans.
4738  if (Exp == IEEEFloat::IEK_NaN) {
4739  IEEEFloat Quiet(Val);
4740  Quiet.makeQuiet();
4741  return Quiet;
4742  }
4743 
4744  if (Exp == IEEEFloat::IEK_Inf)
4745  return Val;
4746 
4747  // 1 is added because frexp is defined to return a normalized fraction in
4748  // +/-[0.5, 1.0), rather than the usual +/-[1.0, 2.0).
4749  Exp = Exp == IEEEFloat::IEK_Zero ? 0 : Exp + 1;
4750  return scalbn(Val, -Exp, RM);
4751 }

4814 // Implement addition, subtraction, multiplication and division based on:
4815 // "Software for Doubled-Precision Floating-Point Computations",
4816 // by Seppo Linnainmaa, ACM TOMS vol 7 no 3, September 1981, pages 272-283.
4817 APFloat::opStatus DoubleAPFloat::addImpl(const APFloat &a, const APFloat &aa,
4818  const APFloat &c, const APFloat &cc,
4819  roundingMode RM) {
4820  int Status = opOK;
4821  APFloat z = a;
4822  Status |= z.add(c, RM);
4823  if (!z.isFinite()) {
4824  if (!z.isInfinity()) {
4825  Floats[0] = std::move(z);
4826  Floats[1].makeZero(/* Neg = */ false);
4827  return (opStatus)Status;
4828  }
4829  Status = opOK;
4830  auto AComparedToC = a.compareAbsoluteValue(c);
4831  z = cc;
4832  Status |= z.add(aa, RM);
4833  if (AComparedToC == APFloat::cmpGreaterThan) {
4834  // z = cc + aa + c + a;
4835  Status |= z.add(c, RM);
4836  Status |= z.add(a, RM);
4837  } else {
4838  // z = cc + aa + a + c;
4839  Status |= z.add(a, RM);
4840  Status |= z.add(c, RM);
4841  }
4842  if (!z.isFinite()) {
4843  Floats[0] = std::move(z);
4844  Floats[1].makeZero(/* Neg = */ false);
4845  return (opStatus)Status;
4846  }
4847  Floats[0] = z;
4848  APFloat zz = aa;
4849  Status |= zz.add(cc, RM);
4850  if (AComparedToC == APFloat::cmpGreaterThan) {
4851  // Floats[1] = a - z + c + zz;
4852  Floats[1] = a;
4853  Status |= Floats[1].subtract(z, RM);
4854  Status |= Floats[1].add(c, RM);
4855  Status |= Floats[1].add(zz, RM);
4856  } else {
4857  // Floats[1] = c - z + a + zz;
4858  Floats[1] = c;
4859  Status |= Floats[1].subtract(z, RM);
4860  Status |= Floats[1].add(a, RM);
4861  Status |= Floats[1].add(zz, RM);
4862  }
4863  } else {
4864  // q = a - z;
4865  APFloat q = a;
4866  Status |= q.subtract(z, RM);
4867 
4868  // zz = q + c + (a - (q + z)) + aa + cc;
4869  // Compute a - (q + z) as -((q + z) - a) to avoid temporary copies.
4870  auto zz = q;
4871  Status |= zz.add(c, RM);
4872  Status |= q.add(z, RM);
4873  Status |= q.subtract(a, RM);
4874  q.changeSign();
4875  Status |= zz.add(q, RM);
4876  Status |= zz.add(aa, RM);
4877  Status |= zz.add(cc, RM);
4878  if (zz.isZero() && !zz.isNegative()) {
4879  Floats[0] = std::move(z);
4880  Floats[1].makeZero(/* Neg = */ false);
4881  return opOK;
4882  }
4883  Floats[0] = z;
4884  Status |= Floats[0].add(zz, RM);
4885  if (!Floats[0].isFinite()) {
4886  Floats[1].makeZero(/* Neg = */ false);
4887  return (opStatus)Status;
4888  }
4889  Floats[1] = std::move(z);
4890  Status |= Floats[1].subtract(Floats[0], RM);
4891  Status |= Floats[1].add(zz, RM);
4892  }
4893  return (opStatus)Status;
4894 }

4896 APFloat::opStatus DoubleAPFloat::addWithSpecial(const DoubleAPFloat &LHS,
4897  const DoubleAPFloat &RHS,
4898  DoubleAPFloat &Out,
4899  roundingMode RM) {
4900  if (LHS.getCategory() == fcNaN) {
4901  Out = LHS;
4902  return opOK;
4903  }
4904  if (RHS.getCategory() == fcNaN) {
4905  Out = RHS;
4906  return opOK;
4907  }
4908  if (LHS.getCategory() == fcZero) {
4909  Out = RHS;
4910  return opOK;
4911  }
4912  if (RHS.getCategory() == fcZero) {
4913  Out = LHS;
4914  return opOK;
4915  }
4916  if (LHS.getCategory() == fcInfinity && RHS.getCategory() == fcInfinity &&
4917  LHS.isNegative() != RHS.isNegative()) {

4920  }
4921  if (LHS.getCategory() == fcInfinity) {

4927  return opOK;

4929  assert(LHS.getCategory() == fcNormal && RHS.getCategory() == fcNormal);
4930 
4931  APFloat A(LHS.Floats[0]), AA(LHS.Floats[1]), C(RHS.Floats[0]),

4937  assert(&Out.Floats[0].getSemantics() == &semIEEEdouble);

4955 APFloat::opStatus DoubleAPFloat::multiply(const DoubleAPFloat &RHS,
4956  APFloat::roundingMode RM) {
4957  const auto &LHS = *this;
4958  auto &Out = *this;
4959  /* Interesting observation: For special categories, finding the lowest
4960  common ancestor of the following layered graph gives the correct
4961  return category:
4962 
4963  NaN
4964  / \
4965  Zero Inf
4966  \ /
4967  Normal
4968 
4969  e.g. NaN * NaN = NaN
4970  Zero * Inf = NaN
4971  Normal * Zero = Zero
4972  Normal * Inf = Inf
4973  */
4974  if (LHS.getCategory() == fcNaN) {
4975  Out = LHS;
4976  return opOK;
4977  }
4978  if (RHS.getCategory() == fcNaN) {
4979  Out = RHS;
4980  return opOK;
4981  }
4982  if ((LHS.getCategory() == fcZero && RHS.getCategory() == fcInfinity) ||
4983  (LHS.getCategory() == fcInfinity && RHS.getCategory() == fcZero)) {
4984  Out.makeNaN(false, false, nullptr);
4985  return opOK;
4986  }
4987  if (LHS.getCategory() == fcZero || LHS.getCategory() == fcInfinity) {
4988  Out = LHS;
4989  return opOK;
4990  }
4991  if (RHS.getCategory() == fcZero || RHS.getCategory() == fcInfinity) {
4992  Out = RHS;
4993  return opOK;
4994  }
4995  assert(LHS.getCategory() == fcNormal && RHS.getCategory() == fcNormal &&
4996  "Special cases not handled exhaustively");
4997 
4998  int Status = opOK;
4999  APFloat A = Floats[0], B = Floats[1], C = RHS.Floats[0], D = RHS.Floats[1];
5000  // t = a * c
5001  APFloat T = A;
5002  Status |= T.multiply(C, RM);
5003  if (!T.isFiniteNonZero()) {
5004  Floats[0] = T;
5005  Floats[1].makeZero(/* Neg = */ false);
5006  return (opStatus)Status;
5007  }
5008 
5009  // tau = fmsub(a, c, t), that is -fmadd(-a, c, t).
5010  APFloat Tau = A;
5011  T.changeSign();
5012  Status |= Tau.fusedMultiplyAdd(C, T, RM);
5013  T.changeSign();
5014  {
5015  // v = a * d
5016  APFloat V = A;
5017  Status |= V.multiply(D, RM);
5018  // w = b * c
5019  APFloat W = B;
5020  Status |= W.multiply(C, RM);
5021  Status |= V.add(W, RM);
5022  // tau += v + w
5023  Status |= Tau.add(V, RM);
5024  }
5025  // u = t + tau
5026  APFloat U = T;
5027  Status |= U.add(Tau, RM);
5028 
5029  Floats[0] = U;
5030  if (!U.isFinite()) {
5031  Floats[1].makeZero(/* Neg = */ false);
5032  } else {
5033  // Floats[1] = (t - u) + tau
5034  Status |= T.subtract(U, RM);
5035  Status |= T.add(Tau, RM);
5036  Floats[1] = T;
5037  }
5038  return (opStatus)Status;
5039 }

5094 APFloat::cmpResult
5095 DoubleAPFloat::compareAbsoluteValue(const DoubleAPFloat &RHS) const {
5096  auto Result = Floats[0].compareAbsoluteValue(RHS.Floats[0]);
5097  if (Result != cmpEqual)
5098  return Result;
5099  Result = Floats[1].compareAbsoluteValue(RHS.Floats[1]);
5100  if (Result == cmpLessThan || Result == cmpGreaterThan) {
5101  auto Against = Floats[0].isNegative() ^ Floats[1].isNegative();
5102  auto RHSAgainst = RHS.Floats[0].isNegative() ^ RHS.Floats[1].isNegative();
5103  if (Against && !RHSAgainst)
5104  return cmpLessThan;
5105  if (!Against && RHSAgainst)
5106  return cmpGreaterThan;
5107  if (!Against && !RHSAgainst)
5108  return Result;
5109  if (Against && RHSAgainst)
5110  return (cmpResult)(cmpLessThan + cmpGreaterThan - Result);
5111  }
5112  return Result;
5113 }
